question: How can candidates of other states (like Karnataka) who have passed 12th standard (2nd PUC) science stream (Domicile of Karnataka) apply for engineering colleges in Tamil Nadu (For eg. Anna University, Madras Institute of Technology etc)?
answers: Greetings! Since you’re from Karnataka (Applies to students from other states too), you will be considered as an out-of-state applicant. There will be a separate application process and counselling session. You will have to keep a tab on the Anna University website (www.annauniv.edu), where all relevant details regarding the out-of-state admission process will be updated. As far as the cut-of is concerned, the marks are calculated the same way they are for students belonging to Tamil Nadu in the following manner: Physics (Your score out of 50) + Chemistry (Your score out of 50) + Mathematics (You Continue ReadingGreetings! Since you’re from Karnataka (Applies to students from other states too), you will be considered as an out-of-state applicant. There will be a separate application process and counselling session. You will have to keep a tab on the Anna University website (www.annauniv.edu), where all relevant details regarding the out-of-state admission process will be updated. As far as the cut-of is concerned, the marks are calculated the same way they are for students belonging to Tamil Nadu in the following manner: Physics (Your score out of 50) + Chemistry (Your score out of 50) + Mathematics (Your score out of 100) = Cut-off / 200 Ex: A student who scores 95/100 in Physics, 90/100 in Chemistry and 80/100 in Mathematics will have a Cut-off of (47.5 + 45 + 80) = 172.5/200 Please do note, that for board where 11th and 12th grade follow a public exam scheme (emphasis on Telangana and Andhra Pradesh), your 11th and 12th grade marks will be considered. For ease, here’s how the conversion of marks happens off for Telangana and Andhra Pradesh*: Ex: You score the following in 11th and 12th: Mathematics 1A/1B/2A/2B: (75/75, 60/75, 70/75, 70/75) = (275/300) = 91.67/100 Physics I/II/Practical**: (60/60, 55/60, 30/30) = (145/150) = 48.38/50 Chemistry I/II/Practical**: (60/60, 50/60, 28/30) = 46/50 M + P + C = (91.6 + 48.38 + 46) = 185.98/200 * Please do note that there could be other states which follow such a system, we have taken these two states as examples only ** At times, practical marks can be excluded, please contact the admissions committee to know more on the same We hope this helped, to know more do ping us. Will be more than happy to help. Cheers!

question: Assuming that I get both VIT and Anna University (CSE group), which of the colleges mentioned above should I join?
answers: Greetings! Jumping from Highschool to University can be an obstacle. However, the most confusing part is deciding on which University program suits you the most, hence helping you shape your career according to your preferences. Since you are clear about the program you would like to pick, here are a few guidelines which might help you decide the university you would want to enroll in: University Accreditation: To begin with, you need to be sure about which of your shortlisted universities has a higher accreditation. Checking this is vital, as it speaks more about the university than the universiContinue ReadingGreetings! Jumping from Highschool to University can be an obstacle. However, the most confusing part is deciding on which University program suits you the most, hence helping you shape your career according to your preferences. Since you are clear about the program you would like to pick, here are a few guidelines which might help you decide the university you would want to enroll in: University Accreditation: To begin with, you need to be sure about which of your shortlisted universities has a higher accreditation. Checking this is vital, as it speaks more about the university than the university does.Government/Private University: It is advised to compare the pros and cons of either type of university, with emphasis on the modus operandi of either type.Class Size: It is often said that having a smaller teacher to student ratio is a win-win for both teachers and students, so that is something you might want to look up at.Quality of Education/Faculty/Campus Resources: This is probably the most vital point of comparison. You would obviously want to look up for the quality of education, faculty, and campus resources offered before you invest four years of your time into any university.Social Life: Social life is something every college fresher looks up to. In the beginning, this might sound very petty, but it is those fests and events that help you socialize with more people and make new friends. Hence, one needs to analyze which institutes could provide you with a better social life.Tuition/Financial Aid/RoI: For what its worth, it is vital to compare and select institutes that might be feasible for you. Those with a more reasonable Return of Investment (RoI), which also provide adequate scholarships and waivers.Location: Being close to home is something every student longs for. Hence, you might want to check up which university is closer to you in terms of distance.Course Catalogue: Looking up the course catalog would help you develop an understanding as to know what you can expect to learn from an academic perspective.Wishing you luck, and if you have decided on joining, we look forward to welcoming you at Anna University! Cheers!

question: What is the easiest way of clearing the Anna University exams?
answers: Being a student, exams prove to be an indispensable one everytime. The most efficient way to clear the exams and come out with flying colours is preparing effectively throughout the semester. Of course, it is not plausible by everyone and at all the time Here are few tips to clear semester exams in Anna University and earn good grades:- 1. The first and foremost method to score good grades in final exams is to have a good and decent internal marks. Internals are an excellent mark boosters for the end semester exams. It is advisable to have an internal of above 30 or 35 out of 50 to obtain good grades. 2. As far as engineering exams in Anna University are concerned, it is recommended to read the syllabus carefully and prioritize what you need to study and how much you exactly need to study to pass the course. 3. While preparing for end semester exams, revisit your assessment question papers as it serves as a better mode of preparation. Also refer to those questions asked in previous year semester exams and try preparing answers for those important questions. 4. Try attending classes regularly as most exams are based on what is covered in the class. So, skipping classes is never advisable. Teachers and Professors usually discuss what is likely to be on an exam during classes, so if you are not in the class, you can't get this crucial information. 5. Take notes and hints on the subject during regular class hours, as handwritten notes prove to be a saviour on the eve of exams. Even if you are not good at taking notes, try to get a hard or soft copy of neat handwritten notes of your friend or classmate and have it ready for preparation before the exam. 6. Taking part in a group study is an excellent opportunity in understanding course material for an exam. Also ensure you're actually studying and not socializing. 7. Apart from exam preparation, you have to ensure that you get enough rest on the day before exams. Eat nutritious food and stay hydrated. Take regular breaks and don't be anxious. 8. Even if you study limited portions, try to revise those topics well so that it will give you confidence to approach exam without fear. 9. In semester exams it is very important that you write the question number for every question you attend. Else it will not be evaluated. Try attempting every question in the paper and please don't omit any question as it may lead to losing marks. Approach the exam in a strategic or logical way by attending easy and well known questions first as it will boost your confidence. Make a tick mark against the questions you attended in the first page of your answer booklet without fail. 10. Ultimately, there's just no shortcut for learning the complete course before the day of exam. If you are on the night before exam and if you feel unprepared, don't panic. The above said plenty, useful and vital methods like handwritten notes, assignment and assessment question papers will help you fetch good grades. ''ALL THE BEST" to clear Anna University exams and get good grades

question: What is meant by IOE (Institute of eminence)? Why Anna university is being offered IOE and Why there is no response from Tamilnadu government? Does it mean that all the colleges affiliated to Anna university get IOE Status?
answers: Institutes of Eminence (IoE) is a recognition scheme for higher education institutes in India, set by the University Grants Commission in 2017. The plan encompasses twenty institutions, 16 of which have already been declared Institutes of Eminence as of August 2019. Recognized institutes are granted more autonomy, both administratively (e.g. setting fees) and academically, and will enjoy better collaboration opportunities with global universities. Public institutions are granted up to ₹1,000 crore (equivalent to ₹12 billion or US$160 million in 2019); no funding is awarded to private institutions. Ten public and ten private institutions are to be identified to emerge as world-class Teaching and Research Institutions. This will enhance affordable access to high quality education for ordinary Indians. Vice chancellor has said the TN government could conditionally accept this status offered without compromising on our 69% reservation policy.

question: What is Anna University’s CEG transportation engineering?
answers: The Division of Transportation Engineering comes under the Department of Civil Engineering , Anna University Chennai. It offers an M.E Programme in Urban Engineering. Introduced in 1974, this programme was designed to train Civil Engineering Graduates to plan, implement, monitor and manage Urban Development activities with special trust on Urban Transportation. This programme was renamed as M.E Transportation Engineering in 2009. The course explains about Traffic Engineering and Management, Transportation Planning, Urban Planning, Sustainable Urban Transport and Development, Road Safety Audit, Transportation Economics, Design and Construction of Flexible and Rigid Pavements, Highway Planning, Maintenance of Roads etc. As per the curriculum, along with the theory courses, the students gain hands on experience by conducting laboratory experiments. Also the students must undergo Practical Training in any one of the reputed organisations. At the end of the Second Semester for a period of four weeks to have an industry related experience.

question: What is the mechanical engineering department without manufacturing engineering?
answers: When you exclude manufacturing part from mechanical engineering, you remain with mechanical design & analysis and thermal design & analysis part. Like design as simple as that of a gear or nut to as complex as that of a car etc and also design of thermal and fluid systems like boilers, pumps, turbines and heat exchangers. However, gone are the earlier days when first engineers designed the things, manufactured them then tested and analysed for failures and made improvement of design and remanufacture and cycle goes on… This is the age of concurrent engineering where one department is meaningless without others, where all under same umbrella, work together and consider limitations of each other at early stages of design to avoid re-modeling after manufacturing to reduce time and cost of developing a new product. Hope you are clarified with the answer.

question: How well do faculties teach in Anna university (CEG and MIT campus)?
answers: Depends on your conception of how teaching ought to be constituted. If you're hoping to have everything laid out for you and have all the subject materials provided solely from an examination point of view, prepare to be a tad disappointed! On the other hand, if you're willing to grasp the fundamental concepts while supplementing the knowledge accrued from lectures with your own research, you're in for a treat. Professors here are mostly PhD holders, so there's no room for doubt regarding their wealth of knowledge in their area of expertise. All you have to do is exploit this resource to your a Continue ReadingDepends on your conception of how teaching ought to be constituted. If you're hoping to have everything laid out for you and have all the subject materials provided solely from an examination point of view, prepare to be a tad disappointed! On the other hand, if you're willing to grasp the fundamental concepts while supplementing the knowledge accrued from lectures with your own research, you're in for a treat. Professors here are mostly PhD holders, so there's no room for doubt regarding their wealth of knowledge in their area of expertise. All you have to do is exploit this resource to your advantage. While the basic framework and concepts of the subject will be explained lucidly in class, you're expected to develop beyond the peripheral material by referring to reference books, doing assignments, delivering presentations, submitting projects (depending on the stream you choose), etc. Any doubts you encounter during self-study can always be clarified with the faculty, they are more than willing to help, in fact, what better way to teach than let you understand what questions need answers? Only when you know what to ask, will you fully appreciate the actual theory of the subject. The best part of CEG is that the professors give you free rein to explore subjects in whichever way you please. There's no restriction pertaining to books to be followed or syllabus to be adhered to. They expect you to expand your understanding by utilizing the time to inculcate the habit of employing creative thought. After all, it wouldn't suffice to regurgitate facts that are well-known already! Wouldn't it be better to give you chance to branch out your critical thinking skills and provide you with a solid foundation that would allow for that to happen? While teaching can be a subjective experience, it's always reasonable to take a step beyond what's handled in the classroom and contribute to one's skillset by dedicated learning and self-study. Hope this helps, good luck! :)

Since you got more than 50% in all the all the subjects you are eligible for other state quota. Scanned copies of 10th and 12th marks sheet and a residence certificate must be uploaded and then if everything is fine with the application the university sends you a counselling letter through mail. question: Anna University MBA: Is it mandatory to attend classes for distance education MBA? And can I opt out of the classes?
answers: To start with, the classes for Anna University's distance education MBA programme are conducted from 8:30 AM to 4:30 PM on Saturdays and holidays, and from 6:15-9:15 PM on weekdays. That being said, it is by no means compulsory to attend these classes, you can definitely opt out of them and learn via self-study. This is extremely suitable for those who wish to juggle both work and education simultaneously, and AU gives room for such provisions. Audio-video home study, live lectures (both online and offline), Edusat Utilization, courseware through Self Instructional mode and unrestrained access to online library are the perks that are automatically packaged with the correspondence course. If you still find yourself in further need of study material, it's advisable to contact the respective MBA faculty for course information. They are always willing to help and make it easier for you to balance a tight study/work schedule. However, you will have to be in college premises to appear for the course examinations. There is absolutely no exemption or special online mode of writing the final examinations, so it is mandatory to be present in campus for the same. Hope this helps you make an informed decision, thanks for the A2A!

question: Can I apply for an MBA in Anna University after the completion of a B.Com?
answers: Yes, i guess so. Check the following- Eligibility Criteria MBA aspirants seeking admission at Anna University must qualify the following eligibility criteria- Candidates must have passed in a recognized Bachelor’s degree of minimum 3 years duration and obtained at least 50 % (45 % in case of candidates belonging to reserved category) at the qualifying examination.Candidates must have passed 10+2+3 or 4 or 5 years pattern or 10+3 years Diploma +3 years pattern or B.E. / B. Tech. / B.Arch. / B. Pharm.AMIE with 2-years regular full-time Teaching experience / Industrial experience in the relevant field after passing all the subjects.Other state candidates can also appear for the entrance test, but the eligibility conditions will be decided by the admission committee.Candidates appearing for their final semester examinations of the qualifying degree may also apply for TANCET 2019.One must appear for TANCET exam for admission in MBA at Anna University. Application Process Steps to follow while registering for TANCET- Open official website of Anna University i.e. www.annauniv.eduClick on TANCET 2020 and Online application form.Create log-in credentials.Proceed to the application form.Provide personal details.Mention the academic qualifications.Select the TANCET exam centresUpload the scanned photograph and signature in the required format.Pay the entrance exam fee of INR 500/- ( 250/- for SC /SCA /ST candidates)Candidates registering for more than one programme have to pay INR 500/- ( 250/- for SC/SCA/ST candidates belonging to Tamil Nadu) for each additional programme through online mode only.

question: Which board is better after the 10th CBSE in Chennai, the state board or CBSE for getting Anna University/MIT/SSN college engineering admissions?
answers: The Central Board of Secondary education is one of the most popular boards of education in the country. Most of the Central government schools like Kendriya Vidyalayas, Navodaya Vidyalayas, Army Public Schools and Air Force Schools fall under the purview of this board. Private schools like the DPS society schools follow this system too. CBSE also conducts JEE-Main currently and used to manage the AIPMT Exams until recently. Overall CBSE is a very decent choice as far as educational boards are concerned. Pros: · If your parents have a transferrable job then CBSE could be ideal for you as almost e Continue ReadingThe Central Board of Secondary education is one of the most popular boards of education in the country. Most of the Central government schools like Kendriya Vidyalayas, Navodaya Vidyalayas, Army Public Schools and Air Force Schools fall under the purview of this board. Private schools like the DPS society schools follow this system too. CBSE also conducts JEE-Main currently and used to manage the AIPMT Exams until recently. Overall CBSE is a very decent choice as far as educational boards are concerned. Pros: · If your parents have a transferrable job then CBSE could be ideal for you as almost every city in India has a CBSE school. · CBSE gives you an edge as the syllabus is followed by most competitive exams like JEE, NEET, etc. · The syllabus has greater flexibility and is more student-friendly as compared to the State Boards. · The emphasis is on the overall growth of students with encouragement in sporting and extracurricular activities. · CBSE certificate is recognized throughout India. Cons: · The approach is more theoretical and not much emphasis is given to real-life concepts behind the science. · Fewer subjects when compared to ICSE. · The focus is mainly on Maths and Science and not much importance given to core English knowledge. · The student picks a stream in 11th & 12th i.e. Science, Commerce, Arts, etc. instead of individual subjects. Each state in India has its board of secondary education. These boards offer curricula to state schools and colleges with pre-university courses. The curriculum of the state board changes according to the state and thus is different in many aspects. There are a few state board colleges that are renowned for their good teaching staff and facilities provided. Pros: · Unique to every state in India. · Easier than other boards with an all-inclusive curriculum that accommodates students of all capabilities. · Ideal for students with other interests such as sports, as the workload is not much. · The curriculum allows you to score high and at the same time focus on extra classes to prepare for entrance exams like JEE. Cons: · The syllabus is not comprehensive enough as compared to other boards. · Traditionally has been more of rote learning. · State language could be mandatory although it varies from state to state. To conclude, the board that you choose doesn’t matter if you can study properly, work hard and score good marks. If your goal is to join ANNA UNIVERSITY colleges or any other institution affiliated to it then my advice is that you should get into a STATE BOARD school since students from there have been known to score higher cutoff marks compared to the CBSE applicants. This increases your chances of securing a seat in a good college with a good branch. Thank You. If you find this answer to be useful then please do UPVOTE!!!

question: What are some tips for getting 1st rank in Anna University?
answers: One of the cliche answers would be: Study smart, not hard. In actuality, it is the truth. Smart in this scenario would be to try and get last year’s question papers and to prepare for both the assessments and semesters using those questions. The pattern will mostly remain the same, and all you have to do is study the lessons in such a way that you can understand them (not memorizing them). Try to actively recall the answers, instead of blindly memorizing them. Try to make the studying process livelier with colorful and bright notes, and mind maps if you are a visual learner. Try to read aloud if  Continue ReadingOne of the cliche answers would be: Study smart, not hard. In actuality, it is the truth. Smart in this scenario would be to try and get last year’s question papers and to prepare for both the assessments and semesters using those questions. The pattern will mostly remain the same, and all you have to do is study the lessons in such a way that you can understand them (not memorizing them). Try to actively recall the answers, instead of blindly memorizing them. Try to make the studying process livelier with colorful and bright notes, and mind maps if you are a visual learner. Try to read aloud if you are an auditory learner or write notes if that’s what helps you learn effectively. Use mnemonics, flashcards, flow charts, etc to reinforce what you have already studied. If you have poor memory, and if revising 2-3 times works, schedule your study plans to accommodate the same. Try to group study for certain subjects that may help. Don’t be afraid to ask for help when required. There is no all-encompassing formula or secret that would give you the 1st rank easily. Learn from your previous mistakes and try to circumvent them this time. Target your weaknesses, and play on your strengths. All the best!

question: What is the digital evaluation of answer sheets announced by Anna University?
answers: The new regulations have brought in a new practice for revaluation, and the usual shroud of mystery has been lifted off this process, allowing us to actually witness and participate in the revaluation. First, you are supposed to apply for a photocopy of your paper for the subjects you want to review. Each photocopy costs ₹300.Next, you’ll receive your photocopies at the ACOE or DCOE offices respectively.After you have reviewed your paper thoroughly, you can apply for revaluation.A committee(consisting of your subject teacher, and a subject expert, and maybe more opinions), will sit down to discuss your paper in your presence! You get to lay claim for your marks in front of them and they can argue against your claim and there are equal chances for you to gain or lose your marks(+ or - 15 is the actual scope for mark changes), depending on the answer you have written versus what was in the expected answer key.

question: Does Anna University have distance education?
answers: Anna University is an institution of higher education that was set up in 1978. The school is based in Chennai, Tamil Nadu.The Centre for Distance Education (CDE) runs Anna University’s distance education program.Anna University is a State University.Anna University offers the following courses through the distance mode.Master of Business Administration (MBA)Master of Computer Application (MCA)M.Sc. Computer ScienceDurationThe MBA and http://M.Sc. Computer Science courses have a minimum of two years (four semesters) duration.Master of Computer Application takes at least three years (six semesters) to complete.EligibilityThe eligibility conditions for distance learning at Anna University include: For MBA, a bachelor degree in any discipline is acceptable.MCA and http://M.Sc. Computer Science courses require any bachelor degree. However, applicants must have studied Mathematics or Statistics as undergraduates or Mathematics at +2 level.As a requirement, candidates must pass the Distance Education Entrance Test (DEET) conducted by the CDE to be considered eligible for any distance program.Also, their bachelor degree must have secured after +2 system or its equivalentFee Structure The fee structure for MBA, MCA, and http://M.Sc. (CS) at Anna University is as follows: Applicants are required to pay a total of Rs. 18,650 for the first semester. This amount covers tuition fee, cost of regulation & syllabus book, refundable caution deposit, admission fee, course development fees, learning aids, facilitation fee, and learning material development.The fee for subsequent semesters is Rs. 12,500 per semester. The payment covers tuition fee, cost of regulation & syllabus book, course development fees, learning aids, facilitation fee, and learning material development.Anna University AccreditationAnna University was accredited as a grade “A” institution by the National Assessment and Accreditation Council (NAAC).Anna University is also accredited by University Grant Commission (UGC).How to Take Admission into Anna University Applicants can apply to Anna University by downloading the application form and prospectus from CDE’s website at www.annauniv.edu/cdeCandidates also obtain the application form in person from the Centre for Distance Education, Anna University, Chennai-600025. The form costs Rs.650. Form fee should be paid by drawing a demand draft in favor of the “The Director, Centre for Distance Education, Anna University, Chennai-600025” payable at Chennai.You can also get the application form in person from Coimbatore, Madurai, Trichy, and Nagercoil study center on making a cash payment of Rs.650.Prospective students can also download the application form from the study centers websites. If you prefer to go this route, you will have to send the completed application along with a demand draft drawn to the tune of Rs.650.

question: How is the induction programme in the Anna University ACT campus?
answers: The induction program for the first years at A.C.Tech campus of Anna University went on for ten days. With a humongous list of fun events and interactive arts, the expectant freshmen were coordinated by their seniors who had tirelessly worked to make this welcoming ceremony seem uncompromisingly a grand gesture. As all things should be, a schedule was set and maintained for all ten days, ensuring the students were always entertained and engaged while in the campus. The days kickstarted with a warm Human Values session for about an hour where students gathered around and spoke their minds out. Every single one of the students spoke in turns, talking about the topic. The respective department staffs provided the best platform for an open interaction amongst the newbies. Based on their interests, the arts class ticked all the boxes of fun for the youngsters. While karate, silambam, western music and dance brought in a battle of the brawns, sewing, clay modelling, handicrafts, terracotta and pencil shading served a clash of art. Towards the end of the program, their works were beautifully showcased for display. The common mess for the boys and girls was where lunch was provided for everyone, even for the day scholars. After the lunch, the students were taken to the Raman Auditorium. The initial three days were spent listening to motivational speakers, eminent personalities and alumni, exclusively for instilling a sense of eye-opening knowledge about life skills. Students were taken on a tour of the campus, their respective departments, making them feel at home. Every single person, including the organizers, the implementers, volunteers, had shed sweat over sweat to assure a safe stay in the campus, contributing to the success of a pleasant orientation event for the freshers.

question: How are the placements for ME embedded systems in CEG Chennai?
answers: M.E Embedded systems is a unique and the most interesting ,booming PG discipline offered under EEE department in College of Engineering Guindy, Anna University. It is a 2-year course consisting of 16 theory courses and 4 laboratory courses. The intake is 25 students. Embedded systems is inclined to more of hardware aspects which include Analog Electronics, Automotive Electronics, Microprocessors and Microcontrollers and is less inclined to software side. It is a course which involves both electricals and Electronics. Every year ,maximum of 15 Students get placed in core companies to make the students aware of the current industry requirements,alumni club meets are conducted.Alumni from M.E Embedded systems share their experiences in industry and also teach them what is expected by the industry.Also guest lectures are conducted now and then by department of ECE and EEE.Highly professional industrial experts from various countries offer guest lectures in the department which offer a great exposure to the students.Every staff in here are highly qualified and explain the core concepts in such a way that bridge the gap between the textbooks and industries. The core companies which hire students from M.E Embedded systems are Valeo, Caterpillar,Volvo, Analog Electronics,Aptiv, Siemens,Nissan,SAP labs etc.The average salary package is 16 to 17 LPA. The students undergo interns in 4th semester which helps them to connect with the industry and have a good learning experience.They are also paid with a high stipend.Also they come up with various projects in hardware side under the guidance and support of staff members.Thus,the placements in M.E Embedded systems are the best of all P.G courses in CEG,AU.

question: What are the pros and cons of the CEG campus at Anna University? People say that they won't teach more there and students only have to study. Is it true?
answers: I will try to be as genuine as possible. The pros and cons will be regarding the 2012–2016 batch of which I was one of the students. Pros:- No bullying or ragging is allowed. There is a strict ban on ragging and the students can complain if they have experienced any.The Technical and Cultural fests are student-run which means, you can be directly a part of one of the teams (of course there will be a shortlist and interviews done for some posts) and you can nurture your talents. But as far as I hear now, these fests would be under control of professors from now on, so I do not know how things areContinue ReadingI will try to be as genuine as possible. The pros and cons will be regarding the 2012–2016 batch of which I was one of the students. Pros:- No bullying or ragging is allowed. There is a strict ban on ragging and the students can complain if they have experienced any.The Technical and Cultural fests are student-run which means, you can be directly a part of one of the teams (of course there will be a shortlist and interviews done for some posts) and you can nurture your talents. But as far as I hear now, these fests would be under control of professors from now on, so I do not know how things are going there.Seniors are chilled and no one needs to be called with suffix “sir.” Everyone calls their seniors like Anna or Akka. There is a humble relationship between seniors and juniors. This helps you to get guidance in all areas.You need not worry about placements, provided you are from circuit branches. On the other hand, the non-circuit branch students will have to struggle but the hard workers usually get placed with flying colors.Being a deemed university, your examination question papers will mostly be set by your faculty. So you will get to know some important topics :PThe students generally come from humble and hardworking backgrounds, it is not at all a tough task to find good friends.Cons:- Well, there is a dress code. Not so strict, but you must wear full pants and shirts for men. Casual wear will also work. Salwar suits for women. Fancy suits will also work.You may have to get settled for a not so important but scoring subject as an elective rather than the one in which you were most interested about. This is because you get so few options for the electives because of less faculty.This one is only for Other State Candidates: You may have to struggle a little bit with the language, but give it 4 to 6 months, you will become so fluent in Tamil that an outsider cannot state the difference between you and a local guy.Finally, getting to the second part of your question, since it is a deemed university, sometimes it happens that the lecturer does not complete the syllabus. This may put extra pressure while placements that you have to study extra or for those who want to do masters. But there are fewer cases of such things happening. This also may happen because the teacher teaches so well but slow that the time runs up. You can always get to the cabin of the faculty to ask doubts, they would be happy to help you. I hope my answer helps. Have a happy stay at CEG.

I will trace back my journey from final year, and then leave it up to decide. Back during the joining and counselling time, when I came to Chennai for the first time, I was awestruck by the huge buildings of the campus. I am from a small town, and all these attracted me very quickly. During the counselling, we were made to run from one building of the campus to another building. I was wondering why didn’t they put up the whole admission shit at one place. Poor management has been the college’s forte from a long time I guess. Anyway, this was my first day’s experience of the college. The hostel life was no good. There were some lame rules regarding the wifi, like, it would start functioning only after 6p.m., and only upto 7a.m. I was like “WHAT???!!!”…who does that, they were charging us nearly one lacs for our hostel, and couldn’t even provide wifi for 24 hours. Like this was not enough, all the social networking apps were banned (WhatsApp, Facebook, Instagram, Hike, Viber (Calling App). Still, we managed to use VPNs to access the apps, but the speed was so shitty, that even 1G (had it ever existed) would have worked better than the wifi. Mess food should not even be discussed I guess; we all know what shit they provide at the mess, at every hostel in the country. Coming to academics. The college had one of the shittiest rules anyone might have had ever heard-collared t-shirts/shirts, jeans and shoes are mandatory. One question to the low standard management of the college, WHY? What makes you think that this will bring discipline to the college? One advice, increase the education quality, don’t make some futile rules, nobody respects you all anyway. The faculties are a lot more degraded. They study from this college, and then teach in this college. This tells you how uneducated they are. We were provided books by college for the first 2 years. Most of the boosk were written and published by the faculties of the college itself. Now imagine-studying from SRM, teaching in SRM, then providing the books to the students written by the teachers of SRM. A nursery grade kid could write a better English than these people, kudos to the education of these faculties (or as they would like to call themselves, “PROFESSORS”). The evaluation system was horrible during our time. This is the break-up of the internal marks Cycle Tests (CT) 1 - 10 marks CT 2 - 10 marks Model Exam - 20 marks Surprise Test (Which we knew about a week before, always) - 5 marks Attendance (Yes, trust me!!!) - 5 marks Aaaaand then we had our end sem exam, which had a weight age of 50 marks. So basically, all we had done during our 4 years, is given exams, every damn month. Labs have never been more useless than here. First, we have to make an ‘observation notebook’. Then, we have to copy the exact same thing in a ‘record file’. In Chandler’s way - “Could anything be more useless?” And it doesn’t end here. After writing the record, you have to get the signature of the Lab In charge (who will make you run behind him like you’re his pet), then the HOD (who doesn’t even care to look what’s inside the file), then a stamp from the department office. And what will they do after all this in the University Practical Exam? Punch a hole in the file and give it back to you. You will suddenly have this irresistible urge of ripping the faculty’s body apart and shredding him/her into pieces and feeding it to the stray dogs. Don’t even think of arguing with the faculties. They will make sure that you don’t pass the semester, and will always find an excuse to kick you out of the class, like you’ve been trying sell his both the kidneys (although eventually you’ll wish to do this :D :P ). Once they will find you in some wrong-doing, they will not leave any stone un turned to serve vengeance. The teaching methodology is like something from the medieval period. They will teach you in the dumbest way possible, making the topic all the more obscure, in such a way that the concept will float in front of your eyes in the most haphazard manner. Many seminars, talks, sessions took place in our college. We were forced to attend those, as the faculties had the bait of attendance. They always said that we have to compulsorily attend the seminar, as attendance will be taken there. We knew that nothing as such would happen, still we always fell into this trap, I don’t know why. You all must have heard of the saying - All that glitters is not gold. This fits perfectly for our ‘Fests’. The more they boasted of it to be a grand event, the more hollow it turned out every time. It’s a humble request - don’t ever think of attending the fests. Instead, utilize the 4–5 days’ holiday and just go to any hill-station nearby (there’re many-Coorg, Munnar, Kodaikanal, Ooty are a few to be named). They could’t even welcome John Abraham properly; he was addressed as a “model, and a bollywood actor”. Shame on you, SRM!!! Skipping the sophomore and the 3rd year, jumping straight to the final year, because the nonsense followed suit. This is when you’ll realize how low this college could sink to create a fake impression in front of companies. Infosys was called for a seminar, which the college tagged as ‘pre-placement talk’. And the company came after almost about a month, for the actual placement process. This was done just to make the company feel that the students are interested in their placements. I am from a non CS/IT/Software branch. So obviously I didn’t know anything about coding. We were made to sit forcefully for TCS recruitment process, and were threatened of being removed from the placements if we didn’t attend their training session. Here’s a screenshot of the mail sent by a faculty of mechanical engineeringbranch to its faculties. You can see what kind of sorcery they were doing for us, in the name of ‘helping the students in the placement process’  Now the mail which was sent to us  This was almost a kind of blackmailing. We had no choice but to sit for the placement. And above that, we were made to learn C programming language in 2 days, with a lecture of 2 hours a day. What on earth made them think it was ever possible? So basically, the faculties were deciding in which company we were supposed to sit. Never even my parents had done this, who are they (faculties) to take decision on this subject? Now this is all one person’s view, which is subjective, let’s go in an objective way. Here are some stats. Prices are not constant Tuition Fees - 2 lacs Books Fees - 15 thousand, which just included 6–7 third class quality books, and a drafter and a cheap geometry box, which broke in the first 2 months of usage. We didn’t get the drafter and the geometry box in the 2nd year. CDC Fees - Another 15 thousand, which included only 2 books of Quantitative Aptitude and 1 book on Verbal Aptitude Hostel And Mess Fees - Approximately 98 thousand. A room which was meant for 2 people previously had started accommodating 3 people Laundry Fees - 5/6 thousand (can’t remember it exactly). It was also compulsory, and we were not allowed to give more that 14 clothes in a week, which included only 1 bed sheet. If clothes were extremely, dirty, they would return them without even washing. Many a times clothes were misplaced. Examination Fees - Approximately 2.3 thousand. This is to be paid before every semester exam. Now the hefty fines. ID Card Lost - 1500. By making a DD, they won’t even accept cash. Renewal of ID Card - 1000. Same process Exam Admit Card Lost - 760 If caught cheating/malpractice in the end semester - 10 thousand. All the papers will be cancelled. So to all those people out there, thinking of joining the “Number 1 Private University In India”, please save your parents’ hard earned money, and join any other, I repeat, ANY OTHER COLLEGE IN INDIA, BUT NOT SRM UNIVERSITY. From, A frustrated Engineer

question: How are the placements for mechanical in the Madras Institute of Technology?
answers: Standard of a college not only depends on placements. Many factors like infrastructure, faculties, department, curriculum, research play a role. If you’re solely relying upon placements, then it’s all in your hand. MIT provides you only a handful of opportunities by roping in few core companies (say 15–20) for technical roles, many IT companies (both service based and product based) and a few other companies for managerial roles. So have a prior plan and then step into  Continue ReadingStandard of a college not only depends on placements. Many factors like infrastructure, faculties, department, curriculum, research play a role. If you’re solely relying upon placements, then it’s all in your hand. question: Which is good for civil engineering, SSN or CEG? I consider SSN a better place for my development as a person. What should I prefer as I am eligible for both?
answers: If you look at NIRF rankings, obviously CEG would be your choice. CEG is a very well-reputed college that is in the heart of the Chennai city. SSN requires at least 3hours of travel daily if you are a dayscholar living in the city. Both colleges are really good in academics and placement aspects. All round development, I feel would be better in SSN. We have a lot of clubs and the sports department is very active. CEG has a lot of opportunities and has tie-ups with IIT-M which makes it even more worthwhile. It also has a wide alumni base spread across the globe, so you'll find that helpful if you  Continue ReadingIf you look at NIRF rankings, obviously CEG would be your choice. CEG is a very well-reputed college that is in the heart of the Chennai city. SSN requires at least 3hours of travel daily if you are a dayscholar living in the city. Both colleges are really good in academics and placement aspects. All round development, I feel would be better in SSN. We have a lot of clubs and the sports department is very active. CEG has a lot of opportunities and has tie-ups with IIT-M which makes it even more worthwhile. It also has a wide alumni base spread across the globe, so you'll find that helpful if you go abroad. CEG has better recognition. SSN also has an active alumni association and tie ups with Carnegie Mellon University, but since it's a relatively new college, it is not as well known as CEG. So, if you wish to go for the brand name, recognition and want to make use of the plethora of opportunities, CEG is definitely a better idea. Since I'm not sure about the civil department placements in core companies in both colleges, I feel it's safer to go with a better recognised college, so that your future academic interests aren't hampered. In a job searching scenario too, CEG students will be preferred more, is what I feel. It's up to you to decide, as both are really good colleges with their own pros and cons. All round development comes only through self effort and the college is just a place where opportunities are given for putting in that effort. SSN is definitely a good college in all aspects, I can proudly say that, as I've been here for a year and I've more or less experienced the SSN life to an extent, where I can safely comment about it. SSN will not be a bad choice for you.

question: What is the minimum cutoff for the GATE score in the TANCET 2019 counselling for Anna University?
answers: The rankings for GATE and TANCET are different. The counselling procedures are held separately. It will be held for GATE candidates first, so the seats are first filled up based on GATE score only. Therefore is it better to atleast attempt GATE. Even a low score candidate of GATE has better chance of getting admission into CEG, Anna University than the topper of TANCET.The first two days of counselling is only for GATE candidates. From third day onwards, the counselling for TANCET candidates are held based on their TANCET score. If all the seats all filled up by GATE candidates in CEG, then TANCET candidates will have no chance. On an average TANCET cutoffs of 40 to 50 or a GATE cutoff from 30 to 35 will suffice to get into CEG for a M.E or M.Tech programme. However, other engineering colleges coming under the umbrella of Anna University have to allot 2 or 3 seats only for GATE candidates. Therefore with respect to other engineering (i.e. excluding CEG), candidates will have better chance based on TANCET ranking. If you want admission in University Departments of Anna University ,it is advisable to write GATE since first preference is given only to GATE candidates and all the seats here are open for GATE students except some self-supporting in few departments. Moreover, the UGC stipend of 12k will be given only to GATE Candidates. In conclusion writing GATE is a must, as you have bright chance of getting an admission into CEG, Anna University. You can also attempt TANCET as scoring is easy and you have a better chance of getting into other engineering colleges.

question: Is it good to pursue an MBA in Correspondance from Anna University, Chennai? Will it hold a high value? Can I have a bright future and a huge career growth and get onsite opportunities?
answers: First, you need to be realistic. A regular MBA or PGDM from a prestigious Tier I or Tier II institution has great value. You can do your MBA in correspondence from Anna University but to expect that it can provide you a bright future and an extraordinary career growth is wishful thinking. Distance MBA courses are done by working professionals who do not have the time or are able to afford the money for the regular one or two year MBA courses. Having said that, do your MBA via correspondence by all means if you take it as a learning opportunity. The creme de la creme of jobs are secured in camp Continue ReadingFirst, you need to be realistic. A regular MBA or PGDM from a prestigious Tier I or Tier II institution has great value. You can do your MBA in correspondence from Anna University but to expect that it can provide you a bright future and an extraordinary career growth is wishful thinking. Distance MBA courses are done by working professionals who do not have the time or are able to afford the money for the regular one or two year MBA courses. Having said that, do your MBA via correspondence by all means if you take it as a learning opportunity. The creme de la creme of jobs are secured in campus placements by students doing regular MBA or PGDM courses in Tier I or Tier II institutions. Studying a MBA course through correspondence would deny you the opportunity to be gained by campus placements. This MBA may reflect in your CV but it is unlikely that most companies would give it more than a passing glance. If you have three to five years of work experience, I would suggest that you do a regular one year MBA or PGDM course from a renowned institution. These institutions have tie-ups with banks to provide education loans which can fund your studies. You need to however have a consistently good academic record starting from your Class X examinations till your graduation and score well either in your CAT or GMAT examinations to be considered for admission to these institutions. Finally, do not fall a prey to ignorant advisors or mushrooming coaching centres promising you the earth if you do your MBA by correspondence from a particular institution. Best of luck.

question: Are TNEA admissions in Tamilnadu for engineering based on aggregate % or only MPC %?

The process of assigning rank The university will collect the cutoff mark score information of all its applicants this year. They will sort the people by the highest score to the lowest score. If two people has the same cutoff marks the following procedure will be followed. If in case of tie in cutoff mark, The fourth optional subject such as computer science, biology will be taken for consideration. The highest scorer will get higher rank.Even if there is a tie in fourth optional subject then the elder candidate based on the age will be given higher rank.Even if the date of birth is same then the random number will be used to sort the rankThe rank list will be published by the Anna University official after the last date for application submission. Source: TNEA 2016 Rank List - Counselling Rank List

question: How is the cutoff for TNEA counselling 2019 calculated for a CBSE student?
answers: The cut off will be calculated by the normalisation process. If the highest mark secured by the student of State Board in Physics is 100 and the highest mark secured by a student of any other Board in the same subject is 90 both the highest marks will be considered to be equal to 100. If a student of the other Board secures 60 marks in Physics when the first mark in Physics in the same Board is 90, 60 marks will be considered to be equal to 66.66 marks as arrived below. (100*60)/90= 66.66 % . After normalisation of marks in the relevant subjects in the qualifying examination conducted by different Boards, the qualified students shall be merged into a common merit list.

question: How did SASTRA consider the CGP score of Andhra students during counseling?
answers: Rank list was prepared on the basis of percentile. In Andhra if Top CGPA is 9.5 then that 9.5 is considered as 100 percentile. If your CGPA is 8.8 then your percentile is 8.8 / 0.95 = 92.6 percentile. Like wise in tamilnadu if top score is 596 then the percentile for 596 scorer is 100. If another guy score 500 then his percentile is 500 / 0.596= 83.8 Like wise the percentile is calculated for every one based on the top score of their state and the rank list produced. Accordingly they call for counselling.

question: What is the syllabus for the TANCET according to Anna University?
answers: TANCET MBA is a two-hour offline (paper-based) examination which is objective in nature. It will be conducted in English with five sections and 100 questions. Apart from the sections, there might be a few questions on verbal activity, basic science as well. The TANCET 2019 question paper will comprise the following sections- Reading ComprehensionEnglish Grammar & UsageAnalysis of Business SituationQuantitative AbilityData SufficiencyTANCET MBA Syllabus 2019 Analysis of Business Situation This section evaluates candidates on the basis of finding a solution from the provided data and situation. They are required to find a solution according to the perspective of business. There are passages of 300 words each and composed of tentatively around 20-30 questions. One needs extensive practice from sample papers and previous years’ question papers to excel in this section. Other entrance examination papers such as XAT and CAT can be of help as well. TANCET MBA Syllabus 2019 - Reading Comprehension This section is composed of around 15-20 questions and evaluates the reading and analytical skills of candidates. So, examinees should read a variety of topics to build proficiency. The reading passages are mostly descriptive, analytical and hypothetical in nature. Some of the topics that one might focus on are - Sports History Technology Politics Business Geography Economics Medicine Environment TANCET MBA Syllabus 2019 - Data Sufficiency In this section, candidates will need to answer approximately 15 - 20 questions. Is yet again a data-centric section and combines day-to-day mathematics with a little blend of critical reasoning. It has a question with two statements. One needs to derive the conclusion of the question from the given set of options written below the same. TANCET MBA Syllabus 2019 - Problem Solving This section has around 20 - 25 mathematical problems. Hence it consists of topics from Quantitative Ability (QA) which are of 10+2 academic standards. One must prepare the following topics for the preparation of this exam. Mensuration Simple Interest Complex Numbers Logarithm Compound Interest Binomial Theorem Percentages LCM and HCF Linear Equations Geometry(focus on Triangles) Mixtures Speed, Time and Distance Ratio and Proportion Surds and Indices Quadratic Equations Number Systems Trigonometry Averages Profit and Loss Time and Work Co-ordinate Geometry Probability Permutation and Combination Progressions Functions and Graphs Inequalities Set Theory Discount Alligations TANCET MBA Syllabus 2019 - Verbal Ability In this section, candidates will need to answer around 20-15 questions. This section evaluates the vocabulary, grammar, punctuation, etc skills in test takers. The primary focus should be laid on error correction of the given statements- Synonyms and AntonymsError correctionParts of speechExceptions in English grammarSentence correctionAnswer credits : careers360

The canteens are situated in places where most of the poor do their work and offer mid-day meals at a reasonable rate of Rs.5. But it is sad to note that the scheme is discontinuing effect from 1st. August 2019. {The Andhra Pradesh government has closed the Anna canteens, which provide meals at Rs 5 for the poor and middle-class people, due to non-renewal of its contract with the Akshaya Patra Foundation. Last year, the state government under N Chandrababu Naidu had launched around 300 Anna canteens after the name of Telugu Desam Party (TDP) founder and former chief minister Nandamuri Taraka Ramarao (NTR). After coming to power, the YSRCP government decided in principle to change the name to Rajanna canteens after the late Rajasekhara Reddy. However, the movement currently stands on hold as the agreement with existing food supplying agency expired on July 31, 2019. The YSRCP government has either done away with or renamed many schemes implemented during the TDP rule. All the schemes announced by the new government during the last two months have been named after Chief Minister YS Jagan Mohan Reddy's father and former chief minister YS Rajasekhar Reddy. Minister for Municipal Affairs Botsa Satyanarayana has said that the closure is temporary and the government will renew the contract agreement with the agency soon. The minister also said that the canteens, which have low response will be closed and the remaining will work, as usual, soon.}(1) So, the poor and middle-class persons have to wait with an empty stomach and wait for the reopening of those canteens and eat all these days food at one go. What an irony. Y.S.jagan should learn from U.P.CM. Yogi Aditya Nath, who distributed School bags with the name of Akhilesh Yadav, the previous CM. Does Y.S.jagan committed to the welfare of the poor or does he committed to get publicity? If the later is the case he will face the same fate as CBN. JAI HIND 1. question: Is it advisable to apply for a review (challenge) in Anna University? I have written well, and I know I'll pass.
answers: You want the honest straight in your face answer? Your not going to like it because the answer is NO. We believe, that it is not at all prudent to apply for a review especially for a paper you know you’ll definitely pass. Let’s break it down:- The new regulations have brought in a new practice for revaluation, and the usual shroud of mystery has been lifted off this process, also allowing us to actually witness the revaluation. First you are supposed to apply for a photocopy of your paper for the subjects you want to review. Each photocopy costs ₹300.Next, you’ll receive your photocopies at the ACContinue ReadingYou want the honest straight in your face answer? Your not going to like it because the answer is NO. We believe, that it is not at all prudent to apply for a review especially for a paper you know you’ll definitely pass. Let’s break it down:- The new regulations have brought in a new practice for revaluation, and the usual shroud of mystery has been lifted off this process, also allowing us to actually witness the revaluation. First you are supposed to apply for a photocopy of your paper for the subjects you want to review. Each photocopy costs ₹300.Next, you’ll receive your photocopies at the ACOE or DCOE offices respectively.After you have reviewed your paper thoroughly, you can apply for revaluation.A committee(consisting of your subject teacher, and a subject expert, and maybe more opinions), will sit down to discuss your paper in your presence! You get to lay claim for your marks in front of them and they can argue against your claim and there is equal chances for you to gain or lose your marks, depending on the answer you have written versus what was in the expected answer key.But if you review the photocopies and realise there is no exact scope for extra marks or there is no genuine mistakes in the correction, PLEASE DON’T APPLY FOR REVAL. Not only will you be paying an extra ₹200 per subject for the revaluation process, you will have to personally present your case in front of a Committee, and be able to prove your claim for those marks! There is the additional fact that the marks can be changed by + or - 15 only, which means the review could go either ways!! Also, these reviews could take place at any times… and may even hamper other aspects like for example; one of the students’ had her revaluation on the day of her assessment which increased her anxiety for both unnecessarily because the revaluation did not yield in any change in her marks in that subject. Sincere advice: it’s not worth it. Paying ₹500 to wait anxiously for an hour or two until you are summoned by the “committee” consisting of your teacher from the previous semester who would definitely be displeased at his/her correction being questioned, along with another teacher who is more inclined to be biased towards the teacher than to be unbiased, and of course, the obvious problem, not actually being able to get more marks that actually benefit your grade overall… Not worth it. Of course there are exceptions; especially when that one or two marks you stake claim for may actually end up boosting your overall grade in the subject, which is pretty rare by the way, but if that’s the case, then proceed, but with extreme caution. All the best.

Professors are also not very smart ask them anything outside the syllabus and they will be unable to answer the question. I met exceptions though my data structures professor is the smartest person ever I met. The whole college management do not believe in over all development of student but in disciplining and controlling their life. As a result of which majority of students are not able to clear the campus placements. The education system of the top college definitely needs to improve a lot. question: Does having an arrear during the first year in Anna University affect our chances of getting placed?
answers: There are two things you must be aware of, one is current arrear and the second one is history of arrear. The current arrear is the one you haven't yet cleared the paper at the time of attending placements. To make it simple, they are the uncleared papers you have in 7th and 8th semesters i.e during the placement season. The history of arrear is the one which you have cleared at the time of placements but still, it will be in the academic records. Every company has a unique criterion for selection of candidates but most of the companies(say 98%) won't take a student who has a current arrear. Wha Continue ReadingThere are two things you must be aware of, one is current arrear and the second one is history of arrear. The current arrear is the one you haven't yet cleared the paper at the time of attending placements. To make it simple, they are the uncleared papers you have in 7th and 8th semesters i.e during the placement season. The history of arrear is the one which you have cleared at the time of placements but still, it will be in the academic records. Every company has a unique criterion for selection of candidates but most of the companies(say 98%) won't take a student who has a current arrear. What is more pathetic is that You wouldn't be able to attend even bulk IT companies. So now coming to point, having an arrear in the first absolutely won't affect your placements but you should clear the paper utmost by 6th sem(for non- circuit branches) or at the end of 2nd year(circuit branches) as the placements start little earlier like having internship opportunities in the third year in great companies, for instance, Microsoft ( for CS and IT). Since having an arrear and clearing it leaves a mark “history of arrear" you wouldn't be able to attend some good companies like Hyundai, Daimler(Benz) etc if you are a mechanical engineer. Hope I am clear with my answer. Any queries can be mentioned in comment.

question: How has the Choice-Based Credit System (CBCS) impacted Anna University?
answers: To those who are not familiar with the term, CBCS was a new regulation introduced by Anna University in its 4 main branches in 2015. It has its own sets of pros and cons. For a change, let's look at the cons first. Cons : One of the main motives of CBCS was to let students choose a staff as per their wishes with an overview that every student gets the faculty that they want. However, the procedure adopted for the same is as messy as IRCTC's ticketing portal, if not worse. Poorly maintained servers and frequent crashing have made the students to sit in front of their computers for hours, or even days, just to select a staff's name and click on Add.Students in rural areas face problems as the internet speed is still not appreciable in few areas. While the university can't be completely blamed for the aforementioned reason, it can at least postpone the enrolment on the reopening day, so that the students can avail the facilities present inside the college's computer laboratories.CBCS started off as a cakewalk for students due to relative grading. The pass mark was 60 percentage of the class average. This meant that, aggregate marks of even 20–30 passed the subject. And then, in the middle of a semester, the University suddenly set 50 as the minimum pass mark to clear the subject. The primary reason for bringing in relative grading was to reduce the burden and workload of the students. But, due to the minimum pass mark amendment, it's primary cause has only been reversed. Before the amendment, there were less than 10 students with arrears in my department. After that, more than 60 students had backlogs. This was just very extreme and the time to adapt was too short.I'm not vouching for bringing in the old system, but the AU can emulate the IIT's and NIT's, where the pass mark is either half of the class highest mark or the class average (the lesser mark is taken into consideration). I'm not entirely sure of the last line but this is what I've heard so. Please feel free to correct me if I'm wrong.Before CBCS, the staffs were assigned on the basis of batches by the department. In this case, the distribution of staffs was completely normal ie) no batch was overdosed with lenient staffs or strict staffs. But, in the new system, if you're just 2 minutes late, you might end up getting all 6 staffs as strict staffs. With the server being unreliable, this issue has happened a lot. My motive is not to criticise a staff who is strict, because everyone evaluates in their own way. But, I've personally seen students put the same effort as others and still end up getting a lesser GPA by 0.75 or 1 than students who are equally capable, because most of their staffs were strict in awarding marks. My point is to make the distribution more normalised.Pros : Your timetable can be flexible as per your interests. CBCS certainly offers its own fair share of freedom to the students, as they can get to decide their timetable.It allows students to gel with their department mates, as the classes are constantly shuffled.It is much more easier to select professional and open elective courses using the server, rather than doing it manually.One final point I'd like to say from my heart is, CBCS has brought too much shuffling and changing in between classes. There's a lack of a constant bunch of people surrounding each other, due to the constant shuffling. This has created a dearth in the class room atmosphere that we used to be pride about in our school days. Ever remembered how you used to shout “12 C is the best?”. Sadly, that doesn't happen here. While CBCS does encourage getting to know more people, my opinion is that having a constant bunch of people around you means a greater deal than the former. Thank you. Hope you took this post in the right way! :)

question: What is the history of College of Engineering, Guindy?
answers: HISTORY OF CEG  Michael Topping (1747–1796) was the Chief Marine Surveyor of Fort St. George in Chennai (then Madras) responsible for founding the oldest modern technical school outside Europe. The Survey School was completed on 17 May 1794, with an initial intake of eight students. In 1858 it became the Civil Engineering School and the College of Engineering in 1861.Topping was also the first full-time modern professional surveyor of India having surveyed the seas off the Coromandel Coast, India’s south-east coast. Topping persuaded astronomer William Petrie to gift his equipment to the governm Continue ReadingHISTORY OF CEG  Michael Topping (1747–1796) was the Chief Marine Surveyor of Fort St. George in Chennai (then Madras) responsible for founding the oldest modern technical school outside Europe. The Survey School was completed on 17 May 1794, with an initial intake of eight students. In 1858 it became the Civil Engineering School and the College of Engineering in 1861.Topping was also the first full-time modern professional surveyor of India having surveyed the seas off the Coromandel Coast, India’s south-east coast. Topping persuaded astronomer William Petrie to gift his equipment to the government and set up the first modern astronomical observatory in Nungambakkam. The school was established in 1792 and Topping was appointed as the British East India Company’s astronomer. Topping died in 1796. CEG began its journey as a school of survey established by the East India Company in 1794 at the Fort St.George Madras. There were only 8 students to start with. It was started by the initiation of Michael Topping an Astronomical Surveyor. He was succeeded by John Golding Ham, who was an Architect and Marine Surveyor. The name of the survey school was changed as Civil Engineering School and moved to Kalasa Mahal buildings in Chepauk in the year 1858. The scope was to train upper and lower subordinates. The College was affiliated to the Madras University in 1862. Civil Engineering was the specialty in those early days. The first set of the students received the DCE degree in 1864. In 1920 the College moved into the sprawling 185 acres campus at Guindy. In 1925, Rao Bahadur G. Nagarathinam Ayyar became the first Indian Principal of the College. This institution became the oldest technical institution in Asia and has several first to its credit.Shifting of the college to Guindy was the impact of conducting the Degree courses in Mechanical Engineering and paved the way for rapid expansion to add some more Degree courses. The Degree courses thus added into curriculum are: Mechanical Engineering – 1894Electrical Engineering – 1930Telecommunication and High ways – 1945Printing Technology 1982 Research Programs were introduced in 1935. Dr. K. L. Rao, former Union Minister for irrigation obtained his first M.Sc. Degree by Research. Miss. Leela George and Miss. A. Lalitha were the first two lady Engineers of Guindy.(1940). In 1942-43, accelerated course was brought into effect with no vacations and 3 batches passed out in two years because of World War II. In 1946 First Ph.D. was obtained by Prof.K.Sukumaran. In 1947 two more colleges were started, one at Ananthapur and another at Vishakhapatnam. But they functioned at Guindy itself for some time for want of infra structural facilities at the new places. In 1957 the intake of students was increased from 175 to 275 for the College. Pre professional course was introduced and the entry level was the newly started Pre-University course. This was later changed to 5 year integrated course. I entered the college in 1957 for the pre professional course and later took Electrical Engineering and passed out in 1962. There were only three branches for us, Electrical, Civil and Mechanical. The branches were selected only in the third year and for the first two years we had to undergo common subjects. There were 2 Girl students in our batch and both took civil Engineering. For the first time one of our batch mate entered into Indian Administrative Service (I.A.S) and another into Indian Foreign Service (I.F.S.) In 1962, due to the Chinese Aggression, many of our batch mates joined the Army Services. Due to rapid industrialization, there were job ample opportunities both in private and Government sectors. We were fortunate to choose the job to our liking. Many of our batch mates went to other countries to seek jobs with higher salaries and perks. All settled well in high positions in life. CEG became the number one college in the State and the Engineering course attracted the best brains of youngsters. CEG was flourishing in Academics, Sports and self employment. Our Engineers had the Ability to design a system, component, or process to meet desired needs within realistic constraints such as economic, environmental, social, political, ethical, health and safety, manufacturability and sustainability. They were also able to function on multidisciplinary teams. In short they become the back bone of our country’s development. In 1978 Perarignar Anna University of Technology (PAUT), subsequently the Anna University, was established with four constituent colleges, 1.CEG 2. MIT 3.ACTech and 4. S.A.P. The Anna University functioned from the Guindy Campus. Mr. P. Sivlingam was the first Vice Chancellor. Dr.Kulandaisamy took over as the second Vice Chancellor and Dr. M.Anandakrishnan was the third Vice Chancellor of the University. New branches of Engineering were introduced in the College. The College offers number of UG and PG courses in different disciplines. The intake was increased every year and it is around 2700 Full time and 550 Part- time UG students as of now and for the PG courses 1740 full time and 453 part time students. In January 2001, all Engineering Colleges in Tamilnadu were affiliated to Anna University. As one of the oldest engineering institutions in the country, CEG has a rich tradition of research, and is dedicated to furthering the frontiers of technology and engineering. Around 13,000 research scholars, pursuing their Ph.D. and M.S./M.Tech at CEG, are afforded a range of opportunities to explore their fields, under the guidance of over 2500 top researchers, and with access to state­ of­ the ­art infrastructure. Often called upon by the Tamil Nadu and Indian government for research purposes, students will work towards sustainable solutions to real world problems. One of the many achievements brought about by the diligence of CEG’s research body, is the launch of the indigenously built microsatellite, ANUSAT, the first such satellite to be built by an Indian university. Under the aegis of ISRO, students and faculty worked tirelessly to build, launch and operate the satellite. CEG is hence the nexus of technology and some of the brightest minds of the country, truly encouraging to an atmosphere of progressive research. CEG engages the research scholars in extensive research activities that extend beyond classrooms. Various specialized Research Centres, with highly experienced faculty, are located around the campus that provides facilities to undertake research in any chosen sphere. Apart from prioritized academic focus, research centres are integral to the comprehensive knowledge, CEG aims to provide. The number of Ph.D. awardees of Anna University from the inception (1978-2013) is 4028, while in the last six convocations (2008-2013) the figure touched, 2793 and in the convocation held in 2013 alone, it is 690. In the 35th convocation, 1010 Ph.D. scholars are awarded degrees. This is an “All time High” number of Ph.D. awardees (for a calendar year) in convocation for Anna University and the highest number of Ph.D. awardees ever achieved by any other Technical University in India. College of Engineering Guindy emerged as the top most college in the State and only the top ranking students are able to get admissions in the College. True to its credit, it has secured the 8th ranking for Engineering and 13th for overall as ranked by National Institutional Ranking Framework (NIRF).The number of private colleges affiliated to Anna University was increased to 590 and the intake of the engineers in 2017 year is about 2 LAKHS .  CEG was established in May of 1794, as a School of Survey with one student in a building near Fort St. George. Founded by Michael Topping, the school became the Civil Engineering School in 1858. Subsequently, CEG was established as a college in 1859 under the Madras University. It was then rechristened as College of Engineering in 1861 with the inclusion of the Mechanical Engineering course.

question: What is the history of College of Engineering, Guindy?

CEG was established under Madras University in 1859 and it was shifted to its current location in Guindy in 1920. question: Is College of Engineering Guindy losing it's standards gradually?
answers: Sadly, Yes. It is due to the following reasons: Resting on past laurels alone, and not being agile enough to develop research and teaching infrastructure.Recruiting faculty only based on recommendations and bribes, and not based on their academic skill set (this practice has been rampant in the last ~ 10 years). CEG should be recruiting good faculty regularly.In spite of being autonomous in its own right, CEG is being subject to too much of interference from the Registrar and Vice Chancellor of Anna University. CEG, MIT, ACT, SAP should be de-affiliated from Anna University, and should form a sContinue ReadingSadly, Yes. It is due to the following reasons: Resting on past laurels alone, and not being agile enough to develop research and teaching infrastructure.Recruiting faculty only based on recommendations and bribes, and not based on their academic skill set (this practice has been rampant in the last ~ 10 years). CEG should be recruiting good faculty regularly.In spite of being autonomous in its own right, CEG is being subject to too much of interference from the Registrar and Vice Chancellor of Anna University. CEG, MIT, ACT, SAP should be de-affiliated from Anna University, and should form a separate university.A pretty arrogant placement cell called CUIC, which focusses only on the companies for the CS industry and lets other departments to fend for themselves. The placements need to be run by the students.Too many students being admitted into the college (The current batch strength of UG is ~ 1,800; CS & IT alone ~ 300; Mechanical, ECE ~ 180). The opening of two Tamil Medium courses (Mechanical and Civil) is also a reason for admission of more students.People mistaking CEG for Anna University, while the latter is not even 50 years old. CEG is 225 years old, but it is not allowed to maintain its separate identity. All the time, even the media shows CEG Red Building to represent Anna University. To all of you, CEG is not ANNA UNIVERSITY.A very rigid course structure, with old-fashioned lab sessions. Most of the labs are not updated with new and current instruments. CEG is already moving towards a flexible credit based system, it is good news. The courses should be regularly updated and the course systems of IISc and IITs can be followed.Students cannot access their department labs whenever they need it. They need to get signatures from the HoD whenever they need to use the machines for some projects or assignments. In this regard, CEG should be flexible and allow its students to use the labs anytime. Just trust the students.Last but not the least, any institute is defined by its alumni network. Currently, the CEGAA is not so strong and united. The alumni association needs to become a stronger body and advise the college administration in academics and industry related issues.Suggest edits if suitable.

The Indian author books are written by Indian authors and can be got from seniors, or in second hand book stores if your budget is tight. The popular websites include pdfdrive.net or Library Genesis Or you could get the hard copy from any seniors or second hand book stores or buy it from online shopping websites. So depending on the textbook you need and it’s availability in stores, or the budget you are under, you could get your books from any of the above or even other new sources. On the other hand if you are a non-AU student and want to have a rough idea of what books are used by the Anna University students then I suggest you google the syllabus for the course of your interest and download the syllabus for that course which will have all the book recommendations and subjects for the course included in it. question: How is the cutoff of the CBSE students at Anna University calculated?
answers: The cutoff of CBSE students at Anna University is calculated by following ways: Maximum marks of Physics,Chemistry are converted to 50.That is the marks you scored in physic and chemstry are halved and added.Mathematics has 100 as maximum marks.The total cutoff marks is 200(maths-100+physic-50+chemistry-50)So, you can calculate your cutoff by adding maths marks out of 100 with physic marks out of 50 and chemistry mark out of 50.
