question: How did the Anna University marks scam come out?
answers: Thousands of students allegedly paid bribes to boost scores The Directorate of Vigilance and Anti-Corruption on Wednesday exposed a major scam in the award of marks during revaluation of answer scripts in the Anna University. Ten academicians, including the former Controller of Examinations Prof. G.V. Uma, were named as accused in the scandal involving a large number of students who allegedly paid bribes to boost their scores during the revaluation of answer scripts. The agency conducted a surprise check on the premises of the suspects and seized incriminating documents, including copies of answer scripts as well as property documents. This is the second time that an incident of this nature has been recorded in Anna University; the last one coming in June 2012. In June 2012, two faculty members had given in writing that they were pressured by some top university officials to award higher marks to certain students during revaluation. However, the accused in that case, who were initially suspended from service, had subsequently gone scot-free due to lack of conclusive evidence. In the latest instance, the First Information Report said in April/May 2017, Dr. Uma, presently Professor, Department of Information Science and Technology, Anna University, conspired with Dr. P. Vijayakumar, Assistant Professor/Dean (in-charge), University College of Engineering, Tindivanam, and Dr. R. Sivakumar, Assistant Professor, University College of Engineering, Tindivanam, and demanded ₹10,000 from each student to boost marks during the revaluation process. Marks forged The suspects allegedly forged answer scripts by altering the marks to benefit the students who paid bribes. The accused persons “destroyed a maximum number of the answer scripts of the students for whom they awarded enhanced marks/pass marks in the revaluation done during August 2017 at Tindivanam and thereby caused disappearance of evidence relating to the criminal offence committed by them.” Preliminary investigation revealed that of the 3,02,380 students who applied for revaluation, 73,733 passed and as many as 16,636 got enhanced marks. Dr. Uma served as Controller of Examinations of Anna University during 2015-18. Dr. Vijayakumar and Dr. Sivakumar were zonal coordinators for the valuation centre at Tindivanam. The remaining accused — R. Sundarajan, M. Mahesh Babu, N. Anbuselvan, C.N. Pratheeba, I. Pragadheeswarar, M. Rameshkannan and S. Ramesh — were professors/lecturers during the same period. “We suspect that several thousands of engineering students paid bribes to boost their scores. Many of them would have graduated as engineers from Anna University. During searches, we seized copies of answer scripts and documents of immovable assets from the residential and office premises of Dr. Uma and others. The accused have been booked under the provisions of the Prevention of Corruption Act, 1988, and also on charges of conspiracy, cheating, forgery and criminal misconduct,” a senior DVAC officer. Evidence destroyed According to the DVAC, the accused destroyed a large number of answer scripts without following the due procedures in a bid to eliminate evidence. However, dozens of answer scripts that were seized clearly revealed the nature of the offence. “If, during the first revaluation, a student gets marks which are 15% more than the original score, the answer script is referred to a third examiner...It is here that the offence took place. Higher marks were awarded to students by forging the answer scripts that were destroyed. Teachers who refused to cooperate and insisted on awarding actual marks were debarred from the process of valuation,” the officer said. When investigators conducted a check by referring some seized answer scripts to independent examiners, it was found that the marks awarded were disproportionately high. During a discreet enquiry prior to registering the case, investigators gathered adequate evidence to prove that students paid bribes to get enhanced marks. The corruption angle was substantiated with other material evidence besides statements of some examiners who admitted to pressure from the suspected officials to commit the offence, sources in the agency added. Investigation was on to examine students, examiners and all others involved in the process of revaluation in the last academic year. Since there was a procedure to get the concurrence of the Passing Board to treat the revaluation marks as equivalent to the original marks obtained by the student and also to recommend action against examiners who were found guilty, the DVAC officials were trying to check if any such complaint was reported to the university authorities and any action contemplated against the examiners or their superiors.

question: What should I know before taking CSE at Anna University in 2018? I have a background in biology, and I don't know a thing about coding.
answers: Hello young padawan, I was in your position about 8 years back. A few things I’d say which helped me navigate the space of being a CS student at CEG are, As someone who has taken Biology in school, you are actually at an advantage compared to many who have taken CS. This might be surprising, but it’s true. The reason for this is that, most of the ones who have taken CS in school are often taught by poor teachers who have shaky fundamentals themselves. Hence, they often learn programs as though it’s some ritual incantation instead of learning it as a set of logically connected steps. Hence, you Continue ReadingHello young padawan, I was in your position about 8 years back. A few things I’d say which helped me navigate the space of being a CS student at CEG are, As someone who has taken Biology in school, you are actually at an advantage compared to many who have taken CS. This might be surprising, but it’s true. The reason for this is that, most of the ones who have taken CS in school are often taught by poor teachers who have shaky fundamentals themselves. Hence, they often learn programs as though it’s some ritual incantation instead of learning it as a set of logically connected steps. Hence, you have the option of starting fresh and learning some basics on your own before you head to college. Head over here- A Gentler Introduction to Programming – freeCodeCamp and start having fun.The faculty at CEG are not going to make learning enjoyable for you. This sucks, but it’s true. So don’t count on learning in the classroom alone. If you’re lucky you might get a few good faculty who understand and teach the curriculum, but that’s not the majority situation.What you study in the classroom and what will help you get a job aren’t always highly correlated, so start cultivating the habit of learning outside the classroom. Places like Codeforces might be helpful.In addition to the points above, don’t get intimidated. Never feel like you’re worse than others out there just because they have a small headstart. There is plenty of time, and in 4 years you can not just catch up, but also do better than your peers. Remember, a little bit of slope makes you for a lot of y-intercept.Good luck! You’re at a good place.

question: What is your opinion about studying at Madras Institute of Technology, Chennai?
answers: Disclaimer: Being a student right now in the college, I hope I don’t offend anyone with the content of this answer. I have had quite a few experiences that I’d love to share from my three years in Madras Institute of Technology, Chennai. There are two aspects of learning - social and academical. The elaboration of each section makes the answer a bit longer than expected. Social Part: I have learnt a lot of things by studying at Madras Institute of technology - from office politics to social relations, from project completion vows to wordly explanation, from friends to acquaintances, from girlfrie Continue ReadingDisclaimer: Being a student right now in the college, I hope I don’t offend anyone with the content of this answer. I have had quite a few experiences that I’d love to share from my three years in Madras Institute of Technology, Chennai. There are two aspects of learning - social and academical. The elaboration of each section makes the answer a bit longer than expected. Social Part: I have learnt a lot of things by studying at Madras Institute of technology - from office politics to social relations, from project completion vows to wordly explanation, from friends to acquaintances, from girlfriends to crushes! The social part of my life has become a complete package because of this college. This college provides you the freedom to experiment. Yes, that’s right. Classes will not be completely from 8.30 AM to 4.30 PM. There will be a lot of free time available for you to hang out with your friends, irrespective of the gender. You can try different hotels, movies, involve in a lot of cultural activities, organize events, walk around the park etc. In short, you can explore a lot in and around college. Except, of course if you can get above 65% attendance, you can get away with it. Co-curricular ActivitiesYou can experiment new ideas with your friends in team projects like Baja, Supra and other stuff which can improve your team management skills and leadership. This allows you to understand how your fellow mates are there with you when you are in difficult situations (I really mean it!). When you are involved in a competition, people who showed promising faces earlier will back away and panic monster sets in. That's when you realize who the genuine people you call friends are and I have found a few (I’ll hold them close to me). Peer to Peer relationship, stress management and even more come into picture and mould you into a forward thinker who knows what to expect from life and plan accordingly. InternshipsBeing a student of the prestigious college makes you eligible for a wide variety of internship and from personal experience, internship is bit overrated during college life. I know it is important to taste work life but if you can't learn anything from it, that is unnecessary and it happens most of the times. At one point, the memories you make going through these internships will be more valuable than the internship itself. Extra-curricular activitiesEvery first year has to go through the toughest physical test of his life in the name of NCC, YRC or NSO. I have experienced a hell of an experience during the summer camp of NSO. Our football coach who accompanied us showed me how ruthless life could be. But he also taught me the greatest lesson of anyone’s life: “Explore your limits”. He used to make us run almost 15 km in the morning including warm-up sessions which also involved running(I have never run more than 200m ever in my life). He sculpted us into footballers in just 10 days. After that, jogging seemed like nothing to us. Team ActivitiesEveryone obviously has dreams that inspire them. I too had one. To achieve it, I needed some time to prepare and this is where the toppers come in. They are just selfless people who gave away weeks of work for me just to edit the calculations and procedure and produce the required work just before the deadline. I will never have enough words to thank them. Without them my dreams of getting into something big would have been shattered by now. Academic Part: The one you guys have been eagerly waiting for. I’m afraid this is going to be a bit disappointing. CurriculumIt is a 10-year-old syllabus which is of no use in the world outside the college campus. I have learnt it the hard way around. It is a potential killer of time and the best way to navigate through this was reading books. I had read my way through them. And MIT OCW lectures were the real deal. FacultyI was a firm believer that good colleges had good faculties. But I was fazed with reality that faculty were not well-versed even in their own principles. I have even thought “what would happen if I took the notes they dearly carried, away from them?”, “Would they be able to continue?” They can’t even elaborate on the notes they prepared. Whenever confronted with good intriguing questions, the answers will be “Ask me later”, “We will see in the next class” (which had never been done) and worst of all is “This question that you are asking doesn’t belong to the engineering domain at all!” These answers had left me bewildered. But, reality is harsh. ProjectsThe Academics that I have faced never left me with challenges. People here will make you believe that doing a quadcopter is a life time achievement. A myth which was busted from my field experience in the competitions I attended. I came to know that some companies were selling it like toys which made me realize how absurd I was. Because, we have never even designed a Paper plane of our own. Quadcopter is something beyond. It is also worthy to mention that we have had professors who had their hands in putting ANUSAT in orbit, but quality has deteriorated quite drastically. Finally!! The Dream BrokenI am an engineering aspirant who had come with dreams of engineering my way into the real world. The only thing I was allowed to do was pass with distinction. “Never ask questions”, “Don't do anything new”, “Don't study from google because it is out of syllabus that everyone follows”. To say that all these just made my passion succumb to death is an understatement. The sad reality is that I still aspire to be an engineer even after completing 3 years of engineering. Note: Contents may hurt a few. I had been brutally honest. These are all objectively viewed experiences and shall not be taken personal.

question: I have got 20 arrears in my 6th sem result, I have only 2 semesters to clear all my papers, how to clear all my arrears and current as well (I am CSE and Anna University)?
answers: Firstly, you have 7 years ( 4 years in college and 3 years out of college)of time to complete your degree. Since you have only 20 backlogs till your 6th sem You need not to worry at all. If you wanna clear all your papers before the final (8th) semester, you need to put a little bit of effort. Find out the backlog subjects in which you have a decent internal marks (>=13) and work on those subjects. List out your backlogs and tabulate all the difficult and easy subjects, as per your knowledge. Schedule your time for doing things other than reading because during the rest of the time you should only prepare for your univ written exams. Concentrate more on maths and the subjects totally based on programming because this step will be really helpful forever even when you try for your job. Yes, Engineering maths is a little bit difficult to grasp within a short period of time but you can manage to get a minimum mark to clear all maths papers. YouTube has many study materials for engineering maths, please visit nptelhrd and download the necessary videos and watch it again and again until you get a clear understanding. When coming to the programming based subjects I would recommend the same (nptelhrd), but you can also manage to clear without the aid of nptelhrd if you know some basics of programming. You can also clear without programs but it depends upon how complicated the questions are. Download all the previous sem question papers and write down the part A and part B questions in a seperate notebook (please don't ignore it is worthy and you can refer it during the final sem if needed). Find the repeatedly asked questions and go through it often. Try to score fullmarks in part A atleast 8. Make sure a minimum of three questions in part B will score 10 marks each. Write something related to the question in part C(if you have one). Disable unnecessary apps in your phone till your exam. No social media apps, no games, no chit cagts and no outings. A minimum of 3 to 4 hours preparation is mandatory. Take a break for 2 to 5 minutes when you feel distracted. Quit the idea of group studies( it does not work out when coming to your scenario) during the time of examination. Get help from seniors who cleared the papers after several attempts because they know the key element. You can clear all your easy papers very easily and few difficult papers for sure within the 7 th sem. May be all the papers if you desired to follow this instructions strictly. Make sure you are scoring the matching external marks in univ written exam as per your existing internal marks. The following table has the list where you can get some idea.  Never ever skip any exam you may have chances to clear some papers by luck if God besides you. If you find any difficulties to appear for all the papers due to lack of time for preparation and revising or very low internal marks, give a try for difficult subjects and push your best. If not, kindly wait till the internal mark drops. Because When you have internal marks in single digit, you need to score more in univ written exam which you can see from the above table. There is another criteria like valuation without internal marks which is described in the following answers. Kindly go through it. In Anna University examinations regulation 2013, what is the minimum marks to get pass without internal after 3 attempts? Kindly upvote and share if you find this answer is useful. Thanks a lot and good luck.

question: What is the aggregate mark in engineering (Anna University)?
answers: Aggregate mark refers to the CGPA we get at the end of every semester. It records our academic progress throughout our college life. It is added cumulatively every semester. Students are graded on a scale of 10 and we don't actually receive our marks. Grades are as follows 91-100 : O - 10 81-90 : A+ - 9 71-80 : A - 8 61-70 : B+ - 7 51-60 : B - 6 Below this mark, it is considered as fail and we have to reappear for that subject. These points mentioned above (next to the grades) are multiplied by the number of credits alloted for that subject and then added for all subjects. This total is divided by the total number of credits and that is your cgpa or aggregate mark for that semester.

question: I have got 7.96 CGPA in Anna university will it be rounded off to 8?
answers: It won't be rounded off. Here's why… Had yours been a CGPA with three or more digits after the decimal point, then it would have been rounded off to two, as Anna University has a CGPA system of 'x.yz', i.e., a mandatory allowance of two decimal places. In short, had your CGPA been 7.995 or more, then it would have been rounded off to 8.00. Since it isn't, it is going to remain 7.96.

question: How best is the research section of CEG?
answers: Research section for ceg and AC Tech both are same I. E Anna university center for research here is the details Centre for Research is functioning from the inception of Anna University on 4th September 1978, offering research programmes in different branches of Engineering, Technology, Architecture and Planning, Science & Humanities and Management Sciences leading to award of Ph.D. and M.S. (By Research) degrees. Faculty members are actively pursuing interdisciplinary and socially relevant research in thrust areas with state–of–the–art equipments in addition to teaching, consultancy and extension activities. This Centre is offering admission to Ph.D. and M.S. (By Research) programmes twice a year. Around 13,000 research scholars are pursuing Ph.D. and M.S./M.Tech. (By Research) programmes. Foreign scholars are admitted through ICCR and QIP scholars have been admitted through AICTE. Full-time research scholars are covered with accident and medical relief policy. In order to further enhance the research activities in Anna University and to become a global competitor in research, meritorious and talented youth with PG degree are attracted by “Anna Centenary Research Corpus” supporting 50 research fellowships every year with a stipend of Rs.16,000/- per month and a contingent grant of Rs.25,000/- per year to each scholar for a maximum period of 3 years. The Centre is looking after the recognition of Departments of various affiliated Engineering Colleges and Industrial Units/R&D centres to do research with this University. It is also providing a platform for the faculty members to interact with other experts in their area of specialization within India and abroad which provide an opportunity for others to understand the research quality of this University and also pave way for scientific collaboration. More than 2500 teaching staffs/experts are recognized as supervisors by the Centre for guiding research scholars. Details required for the scholars/supervisors are posted in the website and periodically updated. Helpdesk is available for scholars to express their problems /to clarify any doubts. Centre is focusing fully on e-Governance such as Online submission of application for Ph.D./M.S. programmes, Online fees collection for the research scholars, Online submission of soft copy of Synopsis and Thesis to speed up the processing. The status of Ph.D. synopsis and thesis submitted by the research scholars can be accessed online from Anna University website. For quick processing of claim bills of the scholars NEFT transfer is adopted and foreign remuneration are settled through SWIFT transfer. The entire gamut of activities of the Centre such as online functionalities, office administration, etc. including the website management have been conceived, designed and developed by in-house team. Evidence of success can be witnessed from drastic reduction in the duration between submission of thesis and award of degree from 8 months to 3 months on an average and increase in number of scholars receiving Ph.D. Degree. The number of Ph.D. awardees of Anna University from the inception (1978-2017) is 7930 while in the last three convocations (2014-2017) is 3902 and in the convocation held in 2017 alone is 1507. In the 35th convocation 1010 Ph.D. scholars are awarded degrees. This is an “All time High” number of Ph.D. awardees (for a calendar year) in convocation for Anna University and the highest number of Ph.D. awardees ever achieved by any other Technical University in India. question: Is there any weightage given for the CBSE/ISC board marks for ranking in counselling by Anna University?
answers: No, anna university dosen't provide any weitage to CBSE/ISC boards. No, it does not differ from state board and other board students, the cut off calculation differs. Matriculation and state board students have advantage over the CBSE students as the marks of CBSE students are normalized with respect to other boards. So CBSE which has tough syllabus than matriculation and State board will be pushed back. For example: If the highest mark secured by the student of State Board of Tamil Nadu in Physics is 100 and the highest marks secured by a student of any other Board in the same subject are 95 both the highest marks will be considered to be equal to 100. If a student of the other Board (consider CBSE student) secures 70 marks in Physics when the first mark in Physics in the same Board is 95, 70 marks obtained by CBSE student will be considered to be equal to 73.68 (100 x 70 / 95 = 73.68%)For CBSE students, the marks obtained by the students in the relevant subjects in the qualifying examination conducted by various Boards or Authority shall be equated with the marks obtained by the students in the same subjects in the qualifying examination conducted by the State Board of Tamil Nadu by adopting the method of normalization.This is the only difference between the CBSE and state board.Good luck :)

question: How decent is the placement of Anna University, Chennai?
answers: The placement process in CEG/MIT starts around September every year and continues till late April. Short version : You've high chances of getting placed in a good company with a really good package if you're from CS/IT departments. Long version: First month of the placement process, you get called by the Centre for University and Industry Collaboration (CUIC) for a 'placement talk' where they'll tell you that the placements are getting harder by the year and they're trying real hard to invite companies for placements. How hard they're trying, you'll never know. Then you get briefed on how to pre Continue ReadingThe placement process in CEG/MIT starts around September every year and continues till late April. Short version : You've high chances of getting placed in a good company with a really good package if you're from CS/IT departments. Long version: First month of the placement process, you get called by the Centre for University and Industry Collaboration (CUIC) for a 'placement talk' where they'll tell you that the placements are getting harder by the year and they're trying real hard to invite companies for placements. How hard they're trying, you'll never know. Then you get briefed on how to prepare for Group Discussions, how to dress for interviews etc. The university follows a simple policy when inviting companies. The companies which offer the largest CTC (Cost To Company ) or Salary get offered the schedule first. This means that the schedule for the first few months are completely filled with software firms like Myntra, Flipkart, Amazon which offer CTC north of 25 LPA. These firms allow students from circuit branches to attend the placement process. So, if you're someone who's from a non circuit branch like Mechanical, Production or Civil, you're sitting duck while your friends in CS are getting placed. However, there are a few companies like Citicorp which allow any branch students to sit for placements. But there's a catch. You need to have a CGPA of 9 or above with no history of arrears to sit in it. This criteria may/ may not be from the company itself. So if you're someone who thought grades don't matter for the first three years, this is the time where it starts to sting a little. Core companies for mechanical departments start trickling in for placements in the following months. Companies like Caterpillar, Titan, Hyundai, Mahindra, L&T, BEL, BPCL, Ford (for ME), Renault Nissan, Saint Gobain, Sundaram Fasteners visited during 2017–18. (Naming only a few here). The average package is around 4 LPA in these companies. Caterpillar, Hyindai, BPCl and BEL offer CTC north of 8LPA. They take 2–6 students in total. There are also companies like Zoho, ZoomRx, TCS, Infosys, Cognizant, Wipro which allow all departments to attend the placements. Ultimately it all comes down to your luck on the particular day that decides whether you get a job or not. If you're a student who's up for counselling and have a chance to choose CS, IT in CEG or MIT, placements shouldn't be a worry factor. If you're thinking of taking Mechanical just because it's a popular department and people say that it's evergreen and there's a sure chance you'll get placed, then you're grossly mistaken. The college offers plenty of opportunity to learn and grow professionally. You can also take a look at the placement statistics available online. But they don't give you picture of the number of students placed in their field of study. As an example, a total of 20 were placed in Manufacturing department. So the statistic will say that 20 were placed out of 45 which is a decent percentage. But the reality is that only 5 of them got a job in a core company and the rest 15 got placed in IT sector. Same goes for other departments like Civil, Industrial and Production. So, you can't take the placement statistics available online in their face value. question: What are the minimum marks for sports reservation in Anna University?
answers: hello, TNEA (Tamil Nadu Educational Association) is held for admission to engineering/ medical courses. The candidates who have sports background can get admission on the basis of the performance in the sport of their choice. There are around 54 sports defined under the sports quota. The candidate who has played the State/ National or International level games can easily get admission under this quota. The sports quota candidates have no admission test. The marks will be awarded according to the position they have obtained in the sport. The candidates will be divided into 6 categories and marks a Continue Readinghello, TNEA (Tamil Nadu Educational Association) is held for admission to engineering/ medical courses. The candidates who have sports background can get admission on the basis of the performance in the sport of their choice. There are around 54 sports defined under the sports quota. The candidate who has played the State/ National or International level games can easily get admission under this quota. The sports quota candidates have no admission test. The marks will be awarded according to the position they have obtained in the sport. The candidates will be divided into 6 categories and marks are different under each category. The candidates who have played International sports have an upper hand as more marks are given to the candidates. Marks Awarded for Sporting Events As per the TNEA ExamScheme, there is a special quota defined for the sports category students. The candidates or sports persons will get the marks against the TNEA 2016 written exam through their performance in the various sports activities. Category 1: The games organized once in 4 years like Olympics, World Cup / Commonwealth Games and Asian games. Category 2: The games which have the participation of at least 6 countries. The sport is recognized by Indian Olympics Association (IOA), Sports Authority of India (SAI) and Ministry of Youth Affairs and Sports (MYAS), Government of India. The candidate can claim this participation only when he/she has also played state or national level championship. Direct participation in the International sports will not be considered. The highest achievement will be considered only in a single tournament. The tournament must be organized in regular fashion by National Olympic Committee (NOCs) authorized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) / International Sports Federations affiliated to the IOC will be considered for award of marks. The candidates who have represented the country or will be representing the country will be given marks each year under the quota. The tournaments approved by the government will be considered. The year dates considered for the application are 01.06.2012 to the Last date of submission of application (01.06.2012 to 31.05.2013, 01.06.2013 to 31.05.2014, 01.06.2014 to 31.05.2015 and 01.06.2015 to the Last date of submission of application) The candidates who have participated in International events have to produce a VISA/Immigration certificate. The time of the event and the dates on the documents must match. In the case of forgery, the candidature will be terminated.

question: Is it worth taking self supporting course in CEG?
answers: There are no differences between regular and self supporting courses/batches except in the amount paid for fees. Self supporting students also attend morning college like the regular students. The evening college is different. In our batch 2012–2016, we were shuffled. Our class had 30 regular and 35–40 self supporting students. And mind you, the first 3 ranks of our ECE batch every year was always amongst the self supporting students. The Gold medallist of our year in ECE was from self-supporting. I can go on and on about placements and students pursuing masters in IIMs, IITs and abroad. All that Continue ReadingThere are no differences between regular and self supporting courses/batches except in the amount paid for fees. Self supporting students also attend morning college like the regular students. The evening college is different. In our batch 2012–2016, we were shuffled. Our class had 30 regular and 35–40 self supporting students. And mind you, the first 3 ranks of our ECE batch every year was always amongst the self supporting students. The Gold medallist of our year in ECE was from self-supporting. I can go on and on about placements and students pursuing masters in IIMs, IITs and abroad. All that matters is do you like the course you are about to take. By the end of shuffle you will forget who was regular and who was in self supporting batches. The college gives you great exposure and opportunities. It is upto you to grab them and move on. You can whine and crib or come out shining. It is the choice you make. So to answer the question, if it is worth to take self supporting in CEG, it is every bit worth it only if you like the course you are about to join and you are willing to go the mile for it. question: How can a non-Tamil Nadu candidate apply for an MTech? Is the TANCET only for a local candidate?
answers: I am a non-TamilNadu candidate who wrote TANCET and pursued M.tech in College of Engineering, Anna University. So I think, I am qualified to help you here. No TANCET is not only for local Tamilnadu candidate. Anyone who wants to pursue post graduation in Tamilnadu colleges can write TANCET. If you have a valid GATE score, you can use that too apply for an MTech and TANCET is not required. But, if you feel your GATE score is less competitive for the branch you wish, you can write TANCET to better your chances. The only difference being, if you get a seat through a GATE score, you would receive st Continue ReadingI am a non-TamilNadu candidate who wrote TANCET and pursued M.tech in College of Engineering, Anna University. So I think, I am qualified to help you here. No TANCET is not only for local Tamilnadu candidate. Anyone who wants to pursue post graduation in Tamilnadu colleges can write TANCET. If you have a valid GATE score, you can use that too apply for an MTech and TANCET is not required. But, if you feel your GATE score is less competitive for the branch you wish, you can write TANCET to better your chances. The only difference being, if you get a seat through a GATE score, you would receive stipend. For TANCET score, you do not get stipend. Each branch will have a defined number as GATE seats. The applications for TANCET is usually issued during the month of March/April and exams will be during May. Exam centers will only be in Tamilnadu. Results will then be declared and you would get your marks. U need to apply for counselling once again wherein they will give tell your rank and your time slot for counselling. The rank will be your overall rank among all candidates applying for M.tech and not based on your individual branch. Since you will be a non-Tamilnadu candidate, you will not be entitled to any reservations. You can select seats available only in General category. All the best.

question: Is it possible to change colleges on the 4th year at Anna University?
answers: Yes! If the college of your choice is willing to accept you and you are able to procure an allotment letter from them and submit it to the necessary authorities at your college(Anna University), and complete the procedures here and get a transfer certificate, then you can transfer to another college during the 4th year also! But don’t forget to consider the actual consequences of you changing colleges, the subjects offered maybe different, the professors and the methods of teaching maybe different and the lab equipments, and the infrastructure of the college may all differ. More importantly the Continue ReadingYes! If the college of your choice is willing to accept you and you are able to procure an allotment letter from them and submit it to the necessary authorities at your college(Anna University), and complete the procedures here and get a transfer certificate, then you can transfer to another college during the 4th year also! But don’t forget to consider the actual consequences of you changing colleges, the subjects offered maybe different, the professors and the methods of teaching maybe different and the lab equipments, and the infrastructure of the college may all differ. More importantly the cultures of the colleges might be different and the values imbibed in one could be poles apart from the ones practiced at the colleges to which the transfer is expected to take place. The student's mindset might be different, and there is the undeniable fact that you’ll be leaving your own friends of three years behind. The college culturals will be different, the contests there, the hostels and the food offered, the fees per semester and other additional costs to be borne… there are a lot more aspects to consider before opting for this transfer option. The process maybe a bit long and hard, but if you are determined, you can make it happen. All the best.

question: Which is the best department to study in MIT-Chennai and CEG-Guindy (Anna Univ-Chennai)?
answers: Disclaimer : This only applies to someone who is actually interested in tech education (not some wanna be film makers who are forced unto engineering). I will cover MIT in this answer. You will know in the end that answer applies to CEG as well. You are someone with high Cut-Off in the range of 197–200. You have no real preference in a specific domain of engineering. You just want to be involved in high-tech and get a very nice pay-check or you want to become rich. Though seems superficial and uninspiring : the above description conforms to a majority of students who gets into MIT. You for some reason (like my close friend who chose MIT because he wanted a train ride every day) decide to try your luck in MIT. You decide to visit MIT like many other students before counselling. The gate welcomes you with a real life model of a satellite designed and launched by MIT. Aeronautical engineering sparks your mind. You tread further and you stumble upon Instrumentation department. Some how you like the classic design of the building. You imagine suffixing your name with Istru engineer. You don’t know that this is Asia’s oldest Instrumentation program (Along with Aero and Production). Then you see a three storied, Department of Rubber & Plastics. That will be the first time you know that such a department exists. You look around yourself and realize every thing is made of these materials nowadays. You keep that as a wild card and stead further. You also see a building with a cool horse design and announces itself as Dept of Automobiles - The Royal Auto.and a group of most visibly proud bunch of students. You see giant lecture hall complexes which houses bulk of first year classes and you see a sea of students coming out of it. That is when you look at the biggest department of MIT- the Electronics and Communications Dept. You wonder why so many people study this course. You don’t realize that building houses one of the most complex and accomplished senior-junior relations in the country. Then you see them and it makes you stop and take a selfie. Those two airforce fighter jets albeit their engines rotting in a MIT dungeon, really makes you think about Aero dept standing behind those jets with their sexy red bricks. You probably know that apart from Dr.APJ Kalam, current ISRO chairman also studied in that building. Then you go past library, and Hangar to look at the old building which houses Production engineering and supposedly a newly introduced Mechanical engineering. The intro scenes of Gautham Vasudev Menon films flashes in your mind. Then you go past a hideous looking work shop and a hangar where students play indoor games. There you go. you see it. It is the dreaded MIT- hostel. Your dad asks the security - where is the rest of the college. He (with broken tamil) will say thats it. You will think - damn this college is small (not realising the true spirit of MIT). But you have not seen the hidden gems : the most important of infinity stones of MITverse. Ofcourse they are hidden and you have to take twisted turns and walk past dreaded grass to find them (:p). Many people almost select them out of luck with a reluctance only to rejoice how their stars aligned. Those are the twin sisters of MIT : Department of Computer Science & Department of Information technology. These departments provides you with excellent and most recent faculty. These departments have the highest package : highest average package : hell the highest number of stream placements. They are the Suresh Raina of MIT making bulk of the placement numbers in the institute. They also have a strong coding culture (I felt), strong management skills training (If you are upto it). They are also have the best GENDER RATIO in the institute. With MIT’s strong senior junior system (T-Series) and a Co-series system : say good bye to your boys/girls school curse. //These only apply to people without specific engineering interest. I chose Rubber & Plastics by interest and it was the best decision I made in my life//

question: In Anna University examinations regulation 2013, what is the minimum marks to get pass without internal after 3 attempts?
answers: Let us discuss about this in detail. Scenario 1. For example, Let us take a paper M3 (TPDE) which is your 3rd Semester paper. If you have internal marks 14 and scored 45 out of 100 (converted into 36 out of 80 ) in univ written exam, then(total 36+14=50) it is considered as Pass (E-Grade Minimum ). This scenario applies to the 3rd sem paper ( eg: m3 ) till your 5th Semester. (up-to three attempts i.e 3rd sem-1st attempt,4th sem-2nd attempt,5th sem-3rd attempt ) Scenario 2. If you are going to appear for the M3 Exam during your 6th Semester ( i.e 4th attempt ), the internal mark for the 3rd Semeste Continue ReadingLet us discuss about this in detail. Scenario 1. For example, Let us take a paper M3 (TPDE) which is your 3rd Semester paper. If you have internal marks 14 and scored 45 out of 100 (converted into 36 out of 80 ) in univ written exam, then(total 36+14=50) it is considered as Pass (E-Grade Minimum ). This scenario applies to the 3rd sem paper ( eg: m3 ) till your 5th Semester. (up-to three attempts i.e 3rd sem-1st attempt,4th sem-2nd attempt,5th sem-3rd attempt ) Scenario 2. If you are going to appear for the M3 Exam during your 6th Semester ( i.e 4th attempt ), the internal mark for the 3rd Semester arrear paper will not be carried to this 6th semester. Its validity is up-to the 5th Semester ( 3rd attempt ). When you don’t have the internal marks criteria, you must score 50 out of 100 in univ written exam, which is considered as Direct Pass ( E grade - Minimum). No conversion of marks from 100 to 80. Scenario 3. Similarly your 7th semester internal marks has the chance to carry up-to the next attempt after the final semester (for understanding consider it as 9th semester ). If you could clear all your papers within this (9th) Semester with Overall 60% (>=) your degree will be awarded with First Class, if lesser than 60% second class. All the internal marks criteria will be dropped during the second attempt after your final semester (for understanding consider it as 10th semester). If you could clear all your papers from the 10th sem to the last chance (6 attempts after final sem, for understanding consider it as 14th semester) your degree will be awarded with second class or lesser, no matter what the percentage you have. So students who have internal marks lesser than 10 ( within the 3 attempts) may find difficulties to clear the papers. Since the written exam mark needs to be matched (100 to 80 Conversion) with the appropriate internal. The attached table shows the mark you need to score for the respective grade and as per your existing internal marks.  If you have good internals (>=13) you can try to clear attempting on or before the third attempt (Scenario 1). If you have a very bad internals , you need to wait till the internal drops (Scenario 2,3) no matter how much effort you put, the internal and external marks does not match sometimes to clear or score a good grade. Some tire 3 engineering colleges and novice professors do this needfully to spoil the student carrier. But clearing the backlogs without internals is a little challenging and it is always a good score since the overall pass mark is scored without the support of internal marks. Even I had many backlogs due to very low internal marks(mostly 4or 5), but i did manage to clear those papers only during the fourth attempt i.e when the internal criteria dropped down (18 out of 21 cleared with less effort , other 3 are little bit difficult and need hardwork to clear). Prepare for exams atleast before one or two months, do not read this blog before exam night.Have a regular practice of writing before examination because the anwser in your brain will not reflect in the answer sheet, sometimes you may start scribbling during the last hour since you lost in touch with your handwriting.Hope this summary is useful. Good Luck.

question: With 591/600 marks in the Andhra Pradesh board, can I get a seat at Anna University?
answers: You can apply to Anna University through All India Quota. The total marks is not important. Only an aggregate of Maths, Physics and Chemistry is important. The method to calculate cut off is as follows. Convert Maths, Physics and Chemistry marks to 200 for each subject. Cut off (out of 200) = (Maths marks/2) + (Physics marks/4) + (Chemistry marks/4) Then an All India Rank List will be provided for other state students. If your rank is decent you can get a seat in Anna University.

answers: Thanks for the A2A College of Engineering, Guindy (CEG) is India’s oldest engineering college started in 1794. The number of illustrious alumni the institution has produced is countless both pre and post independence era. CEG is the only institute to produce two test match cricket captains for India. Verghese Kurien (Founder of Amul), Krish Srikkanth, S. Venkataraghavan, Ex-BCCI President A.C. Muthiah, Actor Nagarjuna, Lyricist Madan Karky, Mu Sigma founder Dhiraj Rajaram, TVS Chairman Venu Srinivasan and the list goes on and on. Even today the institution holds a top 10 ranking in India as per Continue ReadingThanks for the A2A College of Engineering, Guindy (CEG) is India’s oldest engineering college started in 1794. The number of illustrious alumni the institution has produced is countless both pre and post independence era. CEG is the only institute to produce two test match cricket captains for India. Verghese Kurien (Founder of Amul), Krish Srikkanth, S. Venkataraghavan, Ex-BCCI President A.C. Muthiah, Actor Nagarjuna, Lyricist Madan Karky, Mu Sigma founder Dhiraj Rajaram, TVS Chairman Venu Srinivasan and the list goes on and on. Even today the institution holds a top 10 ranking in India as per the latest NIRF ranking for engineering colleges released by the Government of India in 2018. The only problem is the confusion with Anna University MHRD, National Institute Ranking Framework (NIRF) . People need to understand that CEG is a college and Anna University is an affiliating university. And if you will indulge me I will share the full story behind this confusion. The college was affiliated to University of Madras initially and in 1978 it got affiliated to Anna University (along with 3 other premier engineering institutions in Chennai). This did not cause much of a problem and the institution continued to attract the best of talent and faculty and if you go by the kind of P.G. admissions or placements that used to happen then it was creme de la creme. The real confusion started around 2004. There were many politicians wanting to make hay out of the engineering education boom. Engineering colleges were started in makeshift buildings, marriage halls and even cow sheds were getting converted in to engineering colleges. They had only one big issue and that was the reputation of their new colleges. With one magic wand called affiliation these politicians got all colleges in the state affiliated to Anna University. Suddenly they could hide their cowshed colleges and lack of infrastructure under such a strong brand. And the unfortunate downside is the way the 200,000 students affiliated to the University overcrowded the cream 1000 students of the state passing out of CEG. Over the last 10 years many alumni have cried foul and the absence of strong enough push from alumni association and faculty to drive the agenda the brand has remained submerged to some extent. But good talent and potential does not remain hidden for too long. In the last 2 - 3 years, realization has dawned among broader sections of the society including corporates, higher educational institutes and investors and CEG is slowly claiming back its identity. Unscrupulous politicians may come and go but institutions like CEG with a 225 year history cannot be vanquished so easily. Cheers…Hope this helps address your query Disclaimer: I’m a CEG alumni

question: Is Madras Institute of Technology also considered as Anna University? Are CEG and MIT differentiated in terms of the brand value of Anna University?
answers: The ultimate controlling body of Engineering Colleges in Tamil Nadu is ANNA UNIVERSITY. Colleges are classified into following categories. University Departments (UD)Regional Campuses and Aided CollegesAutonomous CollegesSelf Financing Colleges1. University Departments There are four University Departments in Tamil Nadu namely College of Engineering Guindy (CEG), Madras Institute of Technology (MIT), Alagappa College of Technology (ACT) and School of Architecture and Planning (SAP. Out these four campuses, CEG, ACT and SAP are located in Guindy and MIT is located in Chrompet. They have their own  Continue ReadingThe ultimate controlling body of Engineering Colleges in Tamil Nadu is ANNA UNIVERSITY. Colleges are classified into following categories. University Departments (UD)Regional Campuses and Aided CollegesAutonomous CollegesSelf Financing Colleges1. University Departments There are four University Departments in Tamil Nadu namely College of Engineering Guindy (CEG), Madras Institute of Technology (MIT), Alagappa College of Technology (ACT) and School of Architecture and Planning (SAP. Out these four campuses, CEG, ACT and SAP are located in Guindy and MIT is located in Chrompet. They have their own set of departments, syllabus, evaluations(usually by the handling faculties). CEG has several rare courses like Printing Technology, Mining Engineering, Agriculture and Irrigation, etc. MIT has courses like Rubber and Plastics Technology, Automobile Engineering etc. ACT has courses like Chemical, Ceramics Technology etc. 2. Regional Campuses There are four regional campuses of Anna University each at Coimbatore, Madurai, Tirunelveli, and Tiruchirapalli. Aided Colleges There are seven Government Aided colleges in Tamil Nadu. 3. Autonomous Colleges Autonomous colleges get approval from Anna University but after that they have their own set of Administration. Syllabus, Evaluation, etc are done within the college. There are about 20 Autonomous colleges in TN. 4. Self Financing Colleges These colleges are private institutes. They come under Anna University for issuing of degree. Examinations, Evaluations, Syllabus, etc comes under the university and not under the college. For you first question, MIT is part of Anna University. It is one of the four University Departments. Usually each UDs are referred as CEG Campus, MIT Campus, ACT Campus and SAP Campus. Coming to Second question, the main reason is MIT is located at different campus. It is easily differentiated. Outsiders don’t consider MIT as UD(one of the campus) of Anna Univeristy. For them Anna University means the campus at Guindy. There is a discrimination between CEG and MIT at the placement process by some local companies. However, top companies look at the individual rather than the campus. Both CEG and MIT has its own standard.

question: Is a first-year mark considered for overall CGPA at Anna University?
answers: Yes, first year mark is considered in overall CGPA calculation. The average of CGPA obtained by the student at the end of each semester is regarded for the overall CGPA calculation. question: How can we get B.Tech admission at Anna University?
answers: Tamil Nadu Engineering Admissions or TNEA to put it plainly, is a division of Anna University that cares for admissions to B.E and B.Tech courses throughout the state. All colleges which are under Anna University concede understudies dependent on their PCM scores in board examination. In contrast to most different states, there is NO different passageway test in Tamil Nadu. You need to obtain a minimum of 50% marks in each Physics, Chemistry & Maths.The application form should be filled from the official website, once the results are out and to be sent along with the DD.Once all the applicationContinue ReadingTamil Nadu Engineering Admissions or TNEA to put it plainly, is a division of Anna University that cares for admissions to B.E and B.Tech courses throughout the state. All colleges which are under Anna University concede understudies dependent on their PCM scores in board examination. In contrast to most different states, there is NO different passageway test in Tamil Nadu. You need to obtain a minimum of 50% marks in each Physics, Chemistry & Maths.The application form should be filled from the official website, once the results are out and to be sent along with the DD.Once all the applications are received, TNEA will publish a rank list on its website based on PCM marks out of 200. For this, they convert marks in Mathematics out of 100 and combined marks in Physics & Chemistry out of 100.Schedule & venue for the counselling will be notified in advance. You will be called for counselling according to your merit rank, where you will have to decide the college and stream of your preference from the available options.Once you've got your desired college, you will need to pay Rs. 5,000/- to reserve the seat. You'll also be required to get all your original documents verified before the admissions.If you have submitted your original certificates/documents in an Institution then you need to get a bonafide letter from Heat of Institution to that effect.For more information, you can check the official websiteOther modes of entry include Industrial quota, CIWGC (Children of Indian Workers in Gulf Countries), NRI quota and FN quota (Foreign Nationals). Each department has a fixed number of seats for each quota, based on the size of the department

question: What is the eligibility to join Tamil Nadu Engineering colleges for other state students with an HSC score of 51.38% and a PCM score of 105/300? Am I eligible?

The students are called based on their cut off marks wherein they can select from the colleges available for their cutoff marks. The cutoff marks fluctuate every year and cannot be fixed. The cutoff marks are fixed based on your Physics, Chemistry and Mathematics mark with the following share percentage. Physics- 25% Chemistry- 25% Math- 50% That is. F Continue ReadingThe students are admitted through the Single Window Counselling System. The number of seats that are allocated for other state students is very less and the student needs a really good cut off mark to make it to the University Departments -CEG,MIT,ACT. The students are called based on their cut off marks wherein they can select from the colleges available for their cutoff marks. The cutoff marks fluctuate every year and cannot be fixed. The cutoff marks are fixed based on your Physics, Chemistry and Mathematics mark with the following share percentage. Physics- 25% Chemistry- 25% Math- 50% That is. For every mark you lose in Maths reduce 0.5 from the cutoff and for every mark you lose in Physics and Chemistry reduce 0.25 from the cutoff. With the aforementioned PCM marks one can expect a late counselling session.

question: Is it possible to change from Anna University Affiliated College to Deemed College in the 3rd year?
answers: Yes. You can. But transfer will be allowed to another self engineering colleges only. You should submit a form through Principal of your present college to the Anna University, Chennai. You can get the transfer form from the official website of the Anna University. Transfer from college to college or university to university is possible. The procedure for transfer is - Transfer from one College to another: -(1)A student desirous of transfer from one College to another shall apply to the Registrar in the prescribed manner for permission for such transfer. Such applications shall be submitted in  Continue ReadingYes. You can. But transfer will be allowed to another self engineering colleges only. You should submit a form through Principal of your present college to the Anna University, Chennai. You can get the transfer form from the official website of the Anna University. Transfer from college to college or university to university is possible. The procedure for transfer is - Transfer from one College to another: -(1)A student desirous of transfer from one College to another shall apply to the Registrar in the prescribed manner for permission for such transfer. Such applications shall be submitted in every case prior to making the desired transfer and shall furnish valid reasons for the transfer proposed. This Ordinance applies to a transfer during the course of the academic year as well as to a transfer at the end of an academic year.(2) An application for a transfer shall invariably be accompanied by –(i) the written consent of the Principal of the College in which the student is studying;(ii) the written promise of admission from the Principal of the College which he proposes to join, together with an assurance by him that the student, if the transfer is permitted, will be able to continue in his College the course of study already commenced by the student in each subject under each part of the examination; and (iii) a certificate of satisfactory progress and good conduct from the Principal of the College he is leaving.Authority to sanction: -It shall be competent for the Vice-Chancellor to sanction the transfer of a student from one College to another.Combination of attendance:A student who has been permitted by the Vice-Chancellor to be transferred from one College to another, shall apply for combination of the attendance earned by him in the College in which he was studying before such transfer and the attendance that he would be able to earn in the college to which he has been admitted. Every such application shall be accompanied by a chalan receipt for the prescribed fee and shall be sent to the Registrar of the University through the Principal, so as to reach him not later than one month after admission to the new College, and in any case fifteen days before the last date for the receipt of applications for admission to the examinations. Hope it helps… Good Luck :-D

question: Can we get a distinction in Anna University even with the history of arrears?
answers: No, that is not possible. As per Anna University regulations, “A candidate who qualifies for the award of the Degree (vide clause 15) having passed the examination in all the courses in his/her first appearance within the specified minimum number of semesters securing a CGPA of not less than 8.50 shall be declared to have passed the examination in First Class with Distinction. For this purpose the withdrawal from examination (vide clause 17.4) will not be construed as an appearance. Further, the authorized break of study (vide clause18.3) will not be counted for the purpose of classification.” So, a candidate should have no history of arrears, should have passed in first attempt and should have a CGPA of 8.5 and above to get first class with distinction. Cheers, Andy

question: What is the procedure for an OCI holder to get admission into Anna University?
answers: Admission process is explained below.. Admission of students under Children of Indian Workers in Gulf countries (CIWGC) / Non-Resident Indians (NRI) / Foreign Nationals (FN) categories for UG programmes B.E. / B.Tech. Undergraduate Degree programmes for NRI / CIWGC / FN categoris COLLEGE OF ENGINEERING GUINDY CAMPUS ALAGAPPA COLLEGE OF TECHNOLOGY CAMPUS MADRAS INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY CAMPUS Eligibility Criteria for B.E./B.Tech. Degree (Four years): Candidates must have passed the qualifying examination i.e (10+2) of Indian System or its equivalent (completed 12 years of school education) Candidates must have studied in English medium or should have proficiency in English language. The candidate should have passed in all subjects and scored a minimum average of 50 percentage in Mathematics, Physics and Chemistry put together in qualifying examinations. Documents to be submitted Non-Resident Indian (NRI) / Children of Indian Workers in Gulf countries (CIWGC) categories for B.E. / B.Tech. / http://M.Sc. (Five year Integrated): Photocopies of the following documents are to be enclosed along with the application: Recent NRI status certificate of the parent issued by the Indian Embassy of the respective country with their seal (Affidavit of NRI status is not accepted).Employment certificate of the NRI parent. In case of self employment, nature of business, annual income and required proof like Income - Tax paid (for the last 3 years).NRE / NRI bank account of the NRI parent, at least for the last six months.Valid Indian passport of the candidate or Birth Certificate.Valid Indian passport of the NRI parentSchool Transfer Certificate or Migration Certificate or both. If these certificates are not issued in your country, an equivalent transfer certificate from the Principal has to be specially obtained.For 10 + 2 type of Indian Boards OR Foreign Boards:Foreign National Categories for B.E. / B.Tech. / http://M.Sc. (Five year Integrated): Passport of the candidateValid student visa/PIO/OCI card in(In case of Citizen of Indian Origin)Proof of financial support like parents bank statement for the last six months or scholarship offer letter from the Government/other agencies.Certificate showing that the candidate has proficiency in English language.School Transfer Certificate or Migration Certificate or both. If these certificates are not issued in your country, an equivalent transfer certificate from the Principal has to be specially obtained.For 10 + 2 type of Indian Boards OR Foreign Boards:*** If the candidate has studied in a Non-Indian Government board of education system abroad or in India, the eligibility certificate obtained from the Association of Indian Universities (AIU), New Delhi has to be enclosed. Equivalent certificate from AIU has to be given for each individual candidate. Anna University will not accept details from the webites of the boards or any other authorities regarding equivalency. Otherwise, if the Indian Embassy / Consulate in the concerned country provides an eligibility certificate, it can be enclosed. Five year Integrated http://M.Sc. Degree programmes for NRI/CIWGC/FN categories Eligibility Criteria for Five year Integrated http://M.Sc. Degree programmes: A pass in the http://H.Sc. (Academic +2) or equivalent in the first appearance itself, with Mathematics, Physics & Chemistry as three of the four subjects of study prescribed under Part II with the minimum eligibility marks. http://M.Sc. (Electronic Media): A pass in the http://H.Sc. of 10+2 curriculum of any group under Part III (or) its equivalent. The selection of candidates will be based on the percentage of marks obtained in the subjects under Part III (Except Part I - Language and Part II - English). Ranking will be done based on the percentage of average marks obtained in the subjects under Part - III (Except Part I - Language and Part II - English. Documents to be submitted and General information are the same as B.E./B.Tech. programmes as given above for Non - Resident Indian (NRI) / Children of Indian Workers in Gulf countries (CIWGC) / Foreign National categories.
